Today I'll answer all these questions as I discuss the rise and fall of human philosophy.

36
00:02:57,900 --> 00:03:05,900
We humans utilize three massive weapons to navigate the world around us and they're all built in inside us.

37
00:03:05,900 --> 00:03:12,700
As a result we humans are the most sophisticated animal that has ever lived on earth which is incredible.

38
00:03:12,700 --> 00:03:19,700
Next time someone complains about the world being unfair remind them of these amazing tools that every human has.

39
00:03:19,700 --> 00:03:22,700
While other animals don't have all of them.

40
00:03:22,700 --> 00:03:23,700
What are they?

41
00:03:26,400 --> 00:03:34,400
Like all animals the first and most important tool is instinct which most of the time subconsciously shapes our behavior.

42
00:03:34,400 --> 00:03:36,700
We have three basic instincts.

43
00:03:36,700 --> 00:03:38,700
Food, sex, company.

44
00:03:38,700 --> 00:03:41,900
Our first and most important instinct is survival.

45
00:03:41,900 --> 00:03:47,200
We spend a minimum of eight hours or one third of a day working to earn bread.

46
00:03:47,200 --> 00:03:49,300
Imagine we didn't have this instinct.

47
00:03:49,300 --> 00:03:51,400
How would you motivate yourself to work?

48
00:03:51,400 --> 00:03:54,700
Or worse still how would you motivate others to work?

49
00:03:54,700 --> 00:03:57,900
Our survival instinct goes beyond food.

50
00:03:57,900 --> 00:04:03,000
We instinctively avoid danger and anything that threatens our life.

51
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:06,500
Do you think what happened to creatures who didn't have survival instinct?

52
00:04:06,500 --> 00:04:09,700
They needed a self-help book to motivate themselves.

53
00:04:09,700 --> 00:04:19,200
After working eight hours in the evenings we spend hours prowling our city center bars and restaurants in search of a mate or courting a mate.

54
00:04:19,200 --> 00:04:21,700
This is the instinct to procreate.

55
00:04:21,700 --> 00:04:26,000
Of course nowadays we chase a mate for recreational purposes.

56
00:04:26,000 --> 00:04:34,700
The sexual urge is so strongly wired in us especially men that we do it despite the fact that most of us have no plan to have children.

57
00:04:34,700 --> 00:04:43,200
The giant panda is going extinct because they have become too lethargic to have sex so the Chinese government spends lots of money to make more pandas.

58
00:04:43,200 --> 00:04:46,200
Imagine our ancestors didn't want to procreate.

59
00:04:46,200 --> 00:04:47,700
We wouldn't be here.

60
00:04:47,700 --> 00:04:52,400
Our third most basic instinct is seeking the company of other humans.

61
00:04:52,400 --> 00:04:57,600
While men have a stronger sexual urge, women have a stronger urge for company.

62
00:04:57,600 --> 00:05:03,400
Without this instinct we would all end up alone and perhaps would never have a civilization.

63
00:05:03,400 --> 00:05:12,300
Basically our instincts tell us what to do most of the time so we don't have to really think about it or twist our brain to motivate ourselves to do these things.

64
00:05:12,300 --> 00:05:21,500
We instinctively seek food, a partner and a company of other people which allow our conscious brain to save energy on something else.

65
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:33,500
The second weapon in how we navigate life is our emotions which fluctuates day to day and allows us to understand ourselves and those around us.

66
00:05:33,500 --> 00:05:37,000
Our emotions give us hints about our environment.

67
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:43,500
Depending on the time and place we feel angry, sad, frightened, content, happy and ecstatic.

68
00:05:43,500 --> 00:05:52,500
If instincts are like climate that remains stable long term, our emotions are like weather that regulates our daily life.

69
00:05:52,500 --> 00:06:00,000
Our instinctive urges push us to do things to achieve what we want but our environment says yes or no.

70
00:06:00,000 --> 00:06:04,500
For example, seeking a partner we want someone but that person wants someone else.

71
00:06:04,500 --> 00:06:08,500
Here comes our emotions to allow us to cope with this failure.

72
00:06:08,500 --> 00:06:13,500
Or worse still our survival is threatened, our emotions allow us to cope.

73
00:06:13,500 --> 00:06:19,000
So emotions allow us to grow, change and adapt to a new place or a person somewhat quickly.

74
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:24,000
Our emotions are incredibly powerful and motivating us to do things right away.

75
00:06:24,000 --> 00:06:30,000
Negative or positive emotions help us grow and move on and seek a better environment.

76
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:35,500
In fact one of the reasons human conquer the world is because we are not happy where we are for a long time.

77
00:06:35,500 --> 00:06:39,500
Apart from seeking food and safety we are also motivated by boredom.

78
00:06:39,500 --> 00:06:44,500
So our emotions give our conscious mind more free time to do other things.

79
00:06:44,500 --> 00:06:50,000
Instead our emotions do the job for us and motivating us to move, grow and change.

80
00:06:52,000 --> 00:06:55,500
Our third and perhaps the most sophisticated weapon we have is reason,

81
00:06:55,500 --> 00:07:00,000
which is the basis of science and technology which allows civilizations to flourish.

82
00:07:00,500 --> 00:07:02,500
This makes us different from other animals,

83
00:07:02,500 --> 00:07:08,500
our ability to make rational decisions based on informed knowledge and calculated risk.

84
00:07:08,500 --> 00:07:11,500
Instinct and emotions are hardwired in us from birth

85
00:07:11,500 --> 00:07:16,000
but rationality is mostly learned through direct experience of our own

86
00:07:16,000 --> 00:07:22,500
as well as knowledge passed on from our parents and ancestors either orally or in writing.

87
00:07:22,500 --> 00:07:27,000
In fact our rationality is so powerful that it can regulate our instinct and emotions.

88
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:35,000
For example our ability to delay gratification allows us to forgo our present pleasure for future and long term pleasure.

89
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:39,500
Of course not all humans are born equal when it comes to delayed gratification.

90
00:07:39,500 --> 00:07:43,500
Some want their cake right away, some can wait a bit longer

91
00:07:43,500 --> 00:07:48,500
but rationality is an incredible tool for us to look long term not just here and now.

92
00:07:48,500 --> 00:07:52,500
Today we live in a modern world or in the age of rationality.

93
00:07:52,500 --> 00:07:58,000
All our modern technological conveniences are the result of rational science.

94
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:04,000
To sum up humans are hardwired with three incredible tools, instincts, emotions and reason.

95
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:07,000
But where does philosophy fit in this?

96
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:12,000
The word philosophy in Greek means the love of wisdom.

97
00:08:12,000 --> 00:08:15,000
So the first true human science was philosophy.

98
00:08:15,000 --> 00:08:20,000
In fact philosophers were the first rational thinkers who replaced the wise old men or women.

99
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:24,500
They were career thinkers meaning they were known for their thoughts and wisdoms.

100
00:08:24,500 --> 00:08:28,500
So philosophy at its core is a structure rational thinking.

101
00:08:28,500 --> 00:08:31,500
In other words its foundation is rationality.

102
00:08:31,500 --> 00:08:32,500
Why?

103
00:08:32,500 --> 00:08:38,500
We humans developed a more sophisticated brain, perhaps the discovery of fire allowed us to cook our food.

104
00:08:38,500 --> 00:08:44,500
So we could digest our food much quicker as a result we had more time to think.

105
00:08:44,500 --> 00:08:46,500
When you're busy you have no time to think.

106
00:08:46,500 --> 00:08:51,000
In fact I do my thinking while in the toilet because I don't have my smartphone with me.

107
00:08:51,000 --> 00:08:55,000
But this brain good in many ways also came with a disadvantage.

108
00:08:55,000 --> 00:08:59,000
It allows us to develop acute consciousness or self awareness.

109
00:08:59,000 --> 00:09:03,000
The more we understand our environment and our own existence,

110
00:09:03,000 --> 00:09:07,000
the more we start to brood and ask difficult questions.

111
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:13,000
One reason today we control our brain by keeping ourselves busy or hooked on something

112
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:16,000
like work or entertainment or smartphone.

113
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:20,500
With this thinking brain came the most devastating awareness of all death.

114
00:09:20,500 --> 00:09:25,500
Other animals might know death when it comes to them so they instinctively avoid danger.

115
00:09:25,500 --> 00:09:29,500
But we human beasts know death from an early age.

116
00:09:29,500 --> 00:09:33,500
As rational animals we learn from the past to anticipate the future.

117
00:09:33,500 --> 00:09:36,500
In other words we anticipate death.

118
00:09:36,500 --> 00:09:40,500
Despite trying not to think about it we have this fear in the back of our mind.

119
00:09:40,500 --> 00:09:45,500
So this brain of ours became powerful enough to ask important questions.

120
00:09:45,500 --> 00:09:47,000
Why are we here?

121
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:50,000
What is reality and how we know it?

122
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:54,500
Early humans couldn't explain the world, life, the things around them,

123
00:09:54,500 --> 00:09:59,000
especially the sun, the light, seasons, thunder, fire, etc.

124
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:01,500
But the most important question was why death?

125
00:10:01,500 --> 00:10:06,500
This is the main theme of the oldest surviving human story, the Epic of Galgamesh.

126
00:10:06,500 --> 00:10:11,500
Written three or four thousand years ago in which the hero is seeking immortality.

127
00:10:11,500 --> 00:10:13,500
But unfortunately he fails.

128
00:10:13,500 --> 00:10:18,500
So to console himself he builds a city so people could remember him.

129
00:10:18,500 --> 00:10:22,500
Other humans invented gods and religions as security blankets.

130
00:10:22,500 --> 00:10:29,500
In fact the fear of death is so strong in humans that nearly every religion has extended life to afterlife.

131
00:10:29,500 --> 00:10:32,000
So death couldn't scare us anymore.

132
00:10:32,000 --> 00:10:36,000
You could say that human life is so short that we have to have an afterlife.

133
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:39,000
However today most people don't believe in afterlife.

134
00:10:39,000 --> 00:10:45,000
Politically or practically early human societies were ruled by its strongest among them or a group of strong men.

135
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:52,000
Then through the passage of time generations later myths, legends and stories about these strong people were created.

136
00:10:52,000 --> 00:10:59,000
As time passed these legends and myths gave these early strong people titanic god-like roles.

137
00:10:59,000 --> 00:11:05,000
As Italo Calvino once said, folktales are told and retold so many times that they become like pebbles.

138
00:11:05,000 --> 00:11:07,000
Smooth, shiny and perfect.

139
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:14,000
Of course the earliest gods were usually known human phenomena such as the sun, thunder, light, dark, earth and so forth.

140
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:17,000
But over time they took a semi-human form.

141
00:11:17,000 --> 00:11:24,000
Later these ideas became more sophisticated in the form of religion that told sophisticated stories about the origin of life

142
00:11:24,000 --> 00:11:29,000
and also explained death through afterlife, resurrection or reincarnation.

143
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:34,000
But philosophers tried to explain without relying on gods and the supernatural.

144
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:41,000
So they used reason to ask two important questions which became the two main pillars of philosophy.

145
00:11:41,000 --> 00:11:46,000
One what's really out there and two how we know it.

146
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:51,000
So ontology asks what's reality and what things exist or don't exist.

147
00:11:51,000 --> 00:11:55,000
And epistemology asks how we know the world.

148
00:11:55,000 --> 00:12:02,000
So philosophy became a rational tool for humans to understand the world, the meaning of life and how to navigate the world correctly.

149
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:07,000
So early philosophers studied all sciences from stars to frogs and everything in between.

150
00:12:07,000 --> 00:12:15,000
But if you bolded down the three main subjects for philosophers were the physical world, the origin of life and the human mind.

151
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:19,000
In other words, what is the world and how does it work?

152
00:12:19,000 --> 00:12:21,000
What is life and how it works?

153
00:12:21,000 --> 00:12:24,000
And what is human mind and how does it work?

154
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:29,000
So remember these three main topics also play philosophy's own downfall.

155
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:35,000
As time passed, philosophy became too big and too sophisticated so it gave birth to other disciplines.

156
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:39,000
In 15th and 16th century Europe, the first baby was born.

157
00:12:39,000 --> 00:12:43,000
For example Galileo, Copernicus and Newton were the pioneers of physics.

158
00:12:43,000 --> 00:12:51,000
So physicists took over the job of studying the world, the universe, stars, planets and matter as a whole.

159
00:12:51,000 --> 00:12:56,000
A big load was off the philosophers' shoulders and now they focus more on metaphysics.

160
00:12:56,000 --> 00:13:00,000
i.e. the meaning of life and the property of the human mind.

161
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:04,000
Then in the 18th and 19th century however, another baby was born.

162
00:13:04,000 --> 00:13:07,000
Biology took over the job of studying life.

163
00:13:07,000 --> 00:13:11,000
Philosophers no longer needed to dissect, frog to understand the human body.

164
00:13:11,000 --> 00:13:20,000
An important biologist was Charles Darwin, whose theory of evolution by natural selection revolutionized everything we know about life and its origin.

165
00:13:20,000 --> 00:13:24,000
So philosophers were left only to focus on the human mind.

166
00:13:24,000 --> 00:13:28,000
But unfortunately they would snatch that away from philosophers too.

167
00:13:28,000 --> 00:13:34,000
In the late 19th century and early 20th century, philosophy gave birth to its last baby.

168
00:13:34,000 --> 00:13:39,000
We call it psychology that took over the job of studying the human mind.

169
00:13:39,000 --> 00:13:49,000
Two big names are Sigmund Freud and Carl Jung, who both placed importance on the subconscious, the unconscious mind, as greater motivation in human behavior.

170
00:13:49,000 --> 00:13:52,000
So philosophers didn't have to diagnose a human mind anymore.

171
00:13:52,000 --> 00:14:01,000
Few first centuries philosophers were doing the jobs of four people, a physicist, a biologist, a psychologist, and a philosopher.

172
00:14:01,000 --> 00:14:06,000
Now they could enjoy a bit more free time and just sit in their comfy chairs and be philosophers.

173
00:14:06,000 --> 00:14:09,000
After all, everyone has to retire at some point.

174
00:14:09,000 --> 00:14:12,000
But retirement is a tough period in anyone's life.

175
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:18,000
With that things to do, you either face an existential crisis or become lazy and wrought away.

176
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:21,000
So today philosophers have become a bit lazy on the whole.

177
00:14:21,000 --> 00:14:27,000
But also they are a bit out of touch because physics, biology, and psychology have become too specialized.

178
00:14:27,000 --> 00:14:32,000
So philosophers don't have the time to rigorously study all three disciplines.

179
00:14:32,000 --> 00:14:41,000
Also they don't want to get their hands dirty dissecting frogs or spending hours staring at telescopes to study the stars or spend time with mentally ill patients.

180
00:14:41,000 --> 00:14:45,000
So the big question is, what is the purpose of philosophy today?

181
00:14:45,000 --> 00:14:48,000
Should it unify physics, biology, and psychology once again?

182
00:14:48,000 --> 00:14:50,000
Or should it find a new path for itself?

183
00:14:50,000 --> 00:14:59,000
Frederick Nietzsche, the first to fully diagnose the problem of Western philosophy, took philosophy back to the cave through his Zoro Tustra.

184
00:14:59,000 --> 00:15:05,000
Who instead of prophesizing for a single god and the divine tell us about the new type of human.

185
00:15:05,000 --> 00:15:12,000
Ubermansch, who instead of following social values, create new ones through their artistic and philosophical works.

186
00:15:12,000 --> 00:15:16,000
Like the early humans who went to the cave to gain wisdom.

187
00:15:16,000 --> 00:15:20,000
Nietzsche accrued science philosophy for being too rational, not passionate enough.

188
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:26,000
Philosophy is an old man who has produced many amazing kids and now feels lost for a purpose.

189
00:15:26,000 --> 00:15:29,000
Why? It's very simple. It lacks passion.

190
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:33,000
Philosophy started as a rational tool, but it was also its downfall.

191
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:42,000
As we saw, science like physics, biology took over the rational side of philosophy and psychology took over the irrational side of philosophy, to put it very crudely.

192
00:15:42,000 --> 00:15:44,000
What is left? Not much.

193
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:49,000
Is philosophy completely doomed? Well, not quite, I have an answer.

194
00:15:49,000 --> 00:15:54,000
Earlier I mentioned the three big human weapons, instincts, emotions, and reason.

195
00:15:54,000 --> 00:15:58,000
Biology and psychology are taking care of the instinct and the unconscious.

196
00:15:58,000 --> 00:16:04,000
Literature takes care of the human emotions through storytelling, and science takes care of reason.

197
00:16:04,000 --> 00:16:10,000
So is philosophy without a channel? Not quite. My solution is human intuition.

198
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:15,000
There you go. A new philosophy should be based on human intuition.

199
00:16:17,000 --> 00:16:24,000
What is intuition? In a nutshell, instincts are mostly unconscious. Reason is mostly conscious.

200
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:28,000
And emotions are somewhere in the middle. Where does intuition fit in?

201
00:16:28,000 --> 00:16:35,000
It is somewhere between instinct, the hard rock foundation, and reason, the hard rock roof over your head.

202
00:16:35,000 --> 00:16:44,000
So intuition is fluid between two solid surfaces, and also right next to emotions, which is very volatile and even more fluid.

203
00:16:44,000 --> 00:16:49,000
Intuition is a layer deeper than rationality and a level above instinct.

204
00:16:49,000 --> 00:16:55,000
So the new philosophy should be based on intuition because it has direct access to instinct, but also reason.

205
00:16:55,000 --> 00:17:02,000
So in a way, it fits right between the unconscious psychology and the conscious rational sciences like physics and biology.

206
00:17:02,000 --> 00:17:08,000
Scientists don't utilize intuition, so it's a perfect tool for philosophy to understand and explain the world.

207
00:17:08,000 --> 00:17:15,000
Why intuition? An intuition-based philosophy can equip us with a better weapon to cope with suffering.

208
00:17:15,000 --> 00:17:23,000
Rationality through sciences provides us with security, physical utility, and comfort through medicine and technology, like a traditional father would.

209
00:17:23,000 --> 00:17:27,000
Science builds your house, produces your food and clothes.

210
00:17:27,000 --> 00:17:33,000
Emotions provide you with love and care like a traditional mother would, which is literature and stories.

211
00:17:33,000 --> 00:17:44,000
Intuition provides you with the ability to have insights, original ideas, inventiveness, and the ability to connect dots so you have a goal or mission in your life, or relevance in society.

212
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:51,000
Intuition is fast, snappy, and in the moment insight, or genius that allows societies move forward.

213
00:17:51,000 --> 00:17:56,000
In fact, most inventions and discoveries can be attributed to intuition, not rational thinking.

214
00:17:56,000 --> 00:18:04,000
Reason is slow, instinct is too rigid, and emotions cloud your judgment in the moment, but intuition is hit and miss.

215
00:18:04,000 --> 00:18:07,000
When it hits, it sparks a new light.

216
00:18:08,000 --> 00:18:14,000
So, is there a philosopher who bases his philosophy on intuition? I'm glad you asked, yes there is.

217
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:21,000
Henri Bergson, a French philosopher, argued that intuition can vitalize life and give us a new spark.

218
00:18:21,000 --> 00:18:25,000
As Nietzsche argued, reason-based philosophy has become too stale.

219
00:18:25,000 --> 00:18:30,000
For Bergson, intuition is the closest thing to a direct experience of something.

220
00:18:30,000 --> 00:18:35,000
For example, if you want to know a city, you can read all the maps and photographs of the buildings.

221
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:39,000
But it cannot be as good as if you walk the streets of that city.

222
00:18:39,000 --> 00:18:45,000
For example, you can never fully convey the taste of an apple to someone who has never eaten an apple.

223
00:18:45,000 --> 00:18:51,000
That intuitive experience is the closest we humans get to experiencing the taste of an apple.

224
00:18:51,000 --> 00:18:57,000
So, intuition takes us back to our nature, while reason is moving us away from nature.

225
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:02,000
Of course, Bergson is famous for his philosophy of time, creativity, and humor.

226
00:19:02,000 --> 00:19:08,000
He thought intuition and life go together. We know reason tries to tame our natural instincts and emotions.

227
00:19:08,000 --> 00:19:15,000
Rightly so, but it can also go too far in taming us into a docile animal with no vitality.

228
00:19:15,000 --> 00:19:21,000
Bergson's philosophy is called vitalism because he wanted to liberate us from the chain of reason.

229
00:19:23,000 --> 00:19:28,000
So, philosophy started as a rational tool to understand the world, life, and the human mind.

230
00:19:28,000 --> 00:19:32,000
Then it gave away those roles to physicists, biologists, and psychologists.

231
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:36,000
Now it's almost become redundant, so we need a new intuitive philosophy.

232
00:19:36,000 --> 00:19:41,000
But to really understand philosophy and where it's done today, we need to know the history of philosophy.

233
00:19:41,000 --> 00:19:50,000
It's various schools, approaches, eastern, western, humanists, animalists, rationalists, empiricists, social philosophy versus individual philosophy.

