245
00:21:05,000 --> 00:21:07,000
Ontology versus epistemology.

246
00:21:07,000 --> 00:21:10,000
Early philosophy was based on two main questions.

247
00:21:10,000 --> 00:21:16,000
What is reality, which became ontology, and how we know it, which is epistemology.

248
00:21:16,000 --> 00:21:19,000
So ontology asks what is and what is not.

249
00:21:19,000 --> 00:21:24,000
And epistemology asks how we know the thing that exists or does not exist.

250
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:30,000
For example, according to ontological philosophy, humans are either animals or not animals.

251
00:21:30,000 --> 00:21:34,000
If not animals, therefore humans are sacred and fundamentally valuable.

252
00:21:35,000 --> 00:21:42,000
It is accepted as a foundation based on your beliefs, so murdering a human being is one of the most serious crimes.

253
00:21:42,000 --> 00:21:48,000
So, thou shalt not kill is based on ontological notion that human life is sacred.

254
00:21:48,000 --> 00:21:55,000
So ontological philosophy gave birth to sciences in order to understand the world, nature, and human biology.

255
00:21:55,000 --> 00:21:58,000
Aristotle is usually considered the father of modern sciences.

256
00:21:58,000 --> 00:22:02,000
Epistemology, on the other hand, is about how we gather knowledge.

257
00:22:02,000 --> 00:22:05,000
A good example is how we know where we know.

258
00:22:05,000 --> 00:22:12,000
Immanuel Kant said we can never know reality as it is, but we only know things on a limited level.

259
00:22:12,000 --> 00:22:20,000
Why? Because everything has to funnel through the human mind, which is a structure in a way that categorizes things in a certain way.

260
00:22:20,000 --> 00:22:26,000
In other words, we humans put a structure onto the world based on how the human mind works.

261
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:32,000
And the world in itself is unknowable to us because we cannot get out of our human mind.

262
00:22:32,000 --> 00:22:34,000
We can never know the thing in itself.

263
00:22:34,000 --> 00:22:44,000
Michel Foucault went a step further saying that knowledge is power, meaning those in position of science and technology have immense power over others.

264
00:22:44,000 --> 00:22:48,000
He said there is no impartial or power-free science.

265
00:22:48,000 --> 00:22:51,000
Knowledge is a tool in the hands of the powerful.

266
00:22:51,000 --> 00:23:02,000
I'll discuss these more later, so to sum up, ontology is the philosophy of existence, while epistemology is the philosophy of knowledge of that existence.

267
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:05,000
Metaphysics vs Physics

268
00:23:05,000 --> 00:23:11,000
Physics was part of philosophical studies until a few centuries ago, before it became a separate discipline.

269
00:23:11,000 --> 00:23:17,000
Physics mainly studies matter, from the smallest particles to the biggest stars.

270
00:23:17,000 --> 00:23:28,000
Metaphysics, however, is the study of what is beyond the physical world, like ideas, forms, and soul, which is closer to the religious idea of God and the spirits.

271
00:23:28,000 --> 00:23:35,000
A scientist might say human consciousness is rooted in matter and would not exist without brain cells.

272
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:44,000
A metaphysician, on the other hand, might say consciousness is independent of matter, either comes from the higher power or the universe itself is conscious.

273
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:51,000
So, physics is the study of physical matter, while metaphysics is the study of non-physical entities.

274
00:23:53,000 --> 00:23:55,000
Reason vs Logic

275
00:23:55,000 --> 00:23:58,000
Logic has its origins in mathematics.

276
00:23:58,000 --> 00:24:05,000
For example, 2 plus 2 equals 4 is logical, because it follows a very rigid rule that gives you one answer.

277
00:24:05,000 --> 00:24:10,000
But logic is also used as a language of philosophy in order to communicate philosophical ideas.

278
00:24:10,000 --> 00:24:15,000
So, logic is like a foundation on which philosophical debates take place.

279
00:24:15,000 --> 00:24:26,000
Without logic, it is very hard to talk to other people, because in order for a discussion to take place, there has to be some ground basic rules on which all philosophers agree.

280
00:24:26,000 --> 00:24:30,000
So, logic is a method of communication for philosophical arguments.

281
00:24:30,000 --> 00:24:36,000
A good example is Ludwig Wittgenstein, who wanted to make communication as precise as possible.

282
00:24:36,000 --> 00:24:40,000
Also, Bertrand Russell applied mathematics to philosophy.

283
00:24:40,000 --> 00:24:42,000
Reason and logic often go hand in hand.

284
00:24:42,000 --> 00:24:54,000
Since logic is very rigid, like a computer or a game of chess, some argue it limits human ability to express things that go beyond logic, like human emotions and passion.

285
00:24:54,000 --> 00:25:01,000
So, reason or rationality is somewhat more subjective and less scientifically rigorous, like logic.

286
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:06,000
So, reason is often used to persuade people, while logic is outcome is independent.

287
00:25:06,000 --> 00:25:13,000
In other words, if someone uses logic, the outcome might not benefit the argument, while reason is a bit more selective.

288
00:25:13,000 --> 00:25:16,000
So, people use reason to support their argument.

289
00:25:16,000 --> 00:25:22,000
We often use rationalization as a negative form of reason used to persuade people.

290
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:26,000
Logic is more mathematical, while reason is more linguistic.

291
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:30,000
Rationalism versus empiricism.

292
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:37,000
Rationalism is a school of philosophy that believes we understand the world based on our prior ability to reason.

293
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:42,000
It places human beings as a special creature with the ability to know the world,

294
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:48,000
so it has its roots in religion that places human beings as an exception to the animal kingdom.

295
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:52,000
In other words, we are pre-assembled with reason as a tool.

296
00:25:52,000 --> 00:25:56,000
A good example of a rationalist is René Descartes, who famously said,

297
00:25:56,000 --> 00:25:58,000
I think therefore I am.

298
00:25:58,000 --> 00:26:02,000
In other words, the ability to rationalize a thing was enough to know our existence.

299
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:05,000
Leibniz was another famous rationalist.

300
00:26:05,000 --> 00:26:09,000
Empiricism, on the other hand, believes that we know the world through experience.

301
00:26:09,000 --> 00:26:12,000
Our thoughts come as a result of experience.

302
00:26:12,000 --> 00:26:16,000
We know the property of fire because we experience the heat.

303
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:20,000
Babies have no fear of fire inside them from birth.

304
00:26:20,000 --> 00:26:24,000
We experience the pain, therefore we associate fire with pain.

305
00:26:24,000 --> 00:26:29,000
Empiricism is more British, while rationalism is more continental European, mainly French and German.

306
00:26:29,000 --> 00:26:32,000
Famous empiricists were John Locke and David Hume.

307
00:26:32,000 --> 00:26:38,000
Empiricism is also close to pragmatism, most associated with northern European cold climates,

308
00:26:38,000 --> 00:26:41,000
which make you become more practical.

309
00:26:41,000 --> 00:26:45,000
Immanuel Kant combined rationalism and empiricism in his philosophy,

310
00:26:45,000 --> 00:26:48,000
saying that experience is not enough to know the world.

311
00:26:48,000 --> 00:26:52,000
Our own mental structure imposes categories to the world.

312
00:26:52,000 --> 00:26:56,000
In other words, we are not passive, just receiving knowledge through experiences,

313
00:26:56,000 --> 00:26:59,000
but we actively give the world a structure.

314
00:26:59,000 --> 00:27:04,000
He said we cannot know the world as it is, but we know it as our mind's structure.

315
00:27:04,000 --> 00:27:09,000
But our knowledge of the world is limited to the limit of the human mental structure.

316
00:27:09,000 --> 00:27:17,000
Kant's philosophy also gave rise to a phenomenology that studies an object relative to our own experience.

317
00:27:17,000 --> 00:27:19,000
Not the object in of itself.

318
00:27:19,000 --> 00:27:24,000
Kant made a distinction between phenomena, which is how we experience the world,

319
00:27:24,000 --> 00:27:28,000
and phenomena, which is the world in itself, which we can never know.

320
00:27:28,000 --> 00:27:29,000
I'll discuss this later.

321
00:27:29,000 --> 00:27:32,000
So, for rationalists, we know the world because we know.

322
00:27:32,000 --> 00:27:37,000
While for empiricists, we know the world because we experience things.

323
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:41,000
Political philosophy versus ethics.

324
00:27:41,000 --> 00:27:46,000
Ethics is a branch of philosophy that deals with morality, justice, and the legal system.

325
00:27:46,000 --> 00:27:54,000
Ethics is more practical and pragmatic, while political philosophy deals with how societies decide what is right and what is wrong,

326
00:27:54,000 --> 00:27:59,000
and how to live peacefully in a society, and how we punish those who break rules.

327
00:27:59,000 --> 00:28:04,000
As a society evolves, so does its morality, so ethics change.

328
00:28:04,000 --> 00:28:09,000
Something that might be morally acceptable a few centuries ago is not acceptable today.

329
00:28:09,000 --> 00:28:11,000
It also depends on culture.

330
00:28:11,000 --> 00:28:15,000
Some actions are morally right in one culture, but not in another.

331
00:28:15,000 --> 00:28:19,000
Political philosophy is the study of ethics and how it changes.

332
00:28:21,000 --> 00:28:23,000
Egalitarianism versus elitism.

333
00:28:23,000 --> 00:28:31,000
One of the most fundamental questions philosophy has grappled over centuries is the idea of equality versus quality.

334
00:28:31,000 --> 00:28:35,000
Egalitarian philosophy has its roots and religions, such as Christianity,

335
00:28:35,000 --> 00:28:39,000
that all humans have equal dignity and are equally sacred.

336
00:28:39,000 --> 00:28:46,000
But egalitarianism as a philosophy became prominent in Europe during the Enlightenment period of 18th and 19th centuries.

337
00:28:46,000 --> 00:28:55,000
Karl Marx is perhaps the most famous egalitarian philosopher who believed in a communist society where all the resources were shared equally among people.

338
00:28:55,000 --> 00:29:02,000
Elitism, on the other hand, believes that we should run society best in meritocracy, meaning not everyone gets a trophy.

339
00:29:02,000 --> 00:29:07,000
Some people deserve certain rights and privileges because they earn those things.

340
00:29:07,000 --> 00:29:15,000
Elitism has its roots and nature because the animal kingdom runs on a hierarchy, which is part of the evolutionary process.

341
00:29:15,000 --> 00:29:22,000
The most famous elitist philosopher was Friedrich Nietzsche, who incidentally lived around the same time as Marx.

342
00:29:22,000 --> 00:29:28,000
For Nietzsche, great artists and philosophers are not the same as ordinary people, therefore should not be treated so.

343
00:29:28,000 --> 00:29:36,000
Today, the biggest debate in the West is these two schools of thought, equality for all or privileges for those who earn them.

344
00:29:36,000 --> 00:29:42,000
So, egalitarian philosophy believes in equality for all while elitist philosophy believes in merits.

345
00:29:44,000 --> 00:29:46,000
Humanism vs. Utilitarianism

346
00:29:46,000 --> 00:29:52,000
Humanism was born in Europe during the Enlightenment of 18th century, which replaced God with humans.

347
00:29:52,000 --> 00:29:59,000
Instead of the divine being in charge of this planet, we rational humans assumed the ownership of this planet.

348
00:29:59,000 --> 00:30:07,000
Humanists believe in an egalitarian world where all humans are equal, which is rooted in religions and belief that humans are created equal.

349
00:30:07,000 --> 00:30:15,000
But in reality, that is not true. Not all humans are equal. Some are more equal than others, as Giorgio will famously say in Animal Farm.

350
00:30:15,000 --> 00:30:22,000
So, in philosophy, the big question is this. Which humans should determine our social, political and moral values?

351
00:30:23,000 --> 00:30:30,000
Here comes utilitarianism, a branch of humanism that believes in moral values that benefit the greatest number of people.

352
00:30:30,000 --> 00:30:34,000
Not all humans, but the largest majority of humans.

353
00:30:34,000 --> 00:30:38,000
The word utility focuses on how something benefits someone.

354
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:45,000
Pre-enlightenment world was dominated by kings and aristocrats while the majority worked to benefit the minority.

355
00:30:45,000 --> 00:30:52,000
With its roots in Machiavelli's philosophy of end justifies the means, utilitarianism turned it on its head.

356
00:30:52,000 --> 00:30:55,000
Instead of the minority, it focused on the majority.

357
00:30:55,000 --> 00:31:02,000
All actions should be judged by the results that bring the greatest happiness for the greatest number of people.

358
00:31:02,000 --> 00:31:08,000
Utilitarianism was big in England and the most famous one was Jeremy Bentham and later Stuart Mill.

359
00:31:08,000 --> 00:31:13,000
Today's democracy is a little like utilitarian majority rule, at least on paper.

360
00:31:13,000 --> 00:31:22,000
Humanism also gave birth to other isms such as socialism that divides the world based on class, feminism that divides the world based on gender,

361
00:31:22,000 --> 00:31:27,000
and nationalism that divides the world based on nationality or ethnicity or language.

362
00:31:27,000 --> 00:31:33,000
So, humanism puts human in charge of the planet and utilitarianism says the majority of humans.

363
00:31:34,000 --> 00:31:38,000
Postmodernism vs Existentialism

364
00:31:38,000 --> 00:31:47,000
Existentialism popularized after the philosophy of Nietzsche argues that everything starts with our existence, not God or some divine essence.

365
00:31:47,000 --> 00:31:52,000
There is no divine spark, but we just develop a sense of self during our life.

366
00:31:52,000 --> 00:31:55,000
Nothing is given to us prior to our birth.

367
00:31:55,000 --> 00:32:04,000
A famous existentialist philosopher was Jean-Paul Sartre, who said that since we have no essence, we are responsible to make something of ourselves.

368
00:32:04,000 --> 00:32:07,000
He famously said that we are condemned to be free.

369
00:32:07,000 --> 00:32:17,000
While existentialism is concerned with the individual, postmodernism popularized in France is more concerned with communities or cultural groups.

370
00:32:17,000 --> 00:32:27,000
Just like existentialism, it is also rooted in the philosophy of Nietzsche, specifically in his criticisms of a single truth within the Western philosophical tradition.

371
00:32:27,000 --> 00:32:35,000
While existentialism focuses on the condition of the modern existence, postmodernism focuses on the idea of truth and social values.

372
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:39,000
Western philosophy believed in a single truth, like the idea of a single God.

373
00:32:39,000 --> 00:32:49,000
So postmodernism questioned European modernity as a project to unify the whole world around European values of individualism, freedom and materialism.

374
00:32:49,000 --> 00:32:53,000
According to postmodernists, all cultures are as valid as European culture.

375
00:32:53,000 --> 00:32:58,000
Therefore, the world doesn't have to become like Europe to be considered civilized.

376
00:32:58,000 --> 00:33:05,000
Postmodernism is a reaction to modernity, which includes the Enlightenment humanism on the one hand, but colonialism on the other.

377
00:33:05,000 --> 00:33:11,000
Postmodernists put emphasis on power relations, how the weak are forcefully pushed one side.

378
00:33:11,000 --> 00:33:23,000
A famous postmodernist, Michel Foucault, analyzed how the modern state developed effective tools to control people through the prison system, surveillance, mass education and more.

379
00:33:23,000 --> 00:33:34,000
He argued that even sexuality is a power dynamic, men oppressing women, which had a huge influence on the third wave feminism that some argue has become anti-men, anti-masculinity.

380
00:33:34,000 --> 00:33:39,000
Foucault even said all knowledge is tied to power, so there is no independent science.

381
00:33:39,000 --> 00:33:44,000
Therefore, science and technology are tools for the powerful to control the weak.

382
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:53,000
So to sum up, the core philosophy includes ontology of existence and epistemology of knowledge and everything else is a branch of these two.

383
00:33:53,000 --> 00:33:56,000
Physics and metaphysics are part of ontology.

384
00:33:56,000 --> 00:34:03,000
Physics deals with matter, while metaphysics deals with non-material phenomena such as ideas, consciousness.

385
00:34:03,000 --> 00:34:07,000
Reason and logic, rationalism and empiricism are part of epistemology.

386
00:34:07,000 --> 00:34:14,000
Reason is a tool to persuade others, therefore more subjective, while logic is mathematical and impartial.

387
00:34:14,000 --> 00:34:22,000
Rationalism says knowledge comes from within, while empiricism says knowledge only comes from experience or outside.

388
00:34:22,000 --> 00:34:26,000
So outside ontology and epistemology is the philosophy of how to live.

389
00:34:26,000 --> 00:34:34,000
Political philosophy studies morality of good and bad, equality or meritocracy, majority, mass or minority elite.

390
00:34:34,000 --> 00:34:36,000
This is also tied to the meaning of life.

391
00:34:36,000 --> 00:34:43,000
Existentialism puts emphasis on the individual, while postmodernism puts emphasis on the group identity.

392
00:34:43,000 --> 00:34:47,000
Next, I'll look at the differences between Eastern and Western philosophies.

393
00:34:47,000 --> 00:34:51,000
Why one focuses on physical science while the other on mental well-being?

394
00:34:51,000 --> 00:34:59,000
Which should we prioritize, building rockets to conquer space or do yoga for a more peaceful mind on Earth?

395
00:35:02,000 --> 00:35:10,000
In the 1930s, there was an interesting conversation between the greatest Indian poet and philosopher Tagore and the greatest German scientist Einstein.

396
00:35:10,000 --> 00:35:14,000
The conversation centered on the idea of reality, truth and beauty.

397
00:35:14,000 --> 00:35:18,000
Einstein believed in an objective reality outside the human.

398
00:35:18,000 --> 00:35:22,000
While Tagore insisted on the subjective interpretation of reality.

399
00:35:22,000 --> 00:35:29,000
To boil it down, Einstein believed in the old theory of physics, solid matter existing with or without humans.

400
00:35:29,000 --> 00:35:38,000
While Tagore was alluding to the mysterious theory of quantum physics, that our perception or observation of matter is never really objective.

401
00:35:38,000 --> 00:35:43,000
The conversation illustrated the differences in Eastern and Western ways of thinking about reality.

402
00:35:43,000 --> 00:35:47,000
One more pragmatic, while the other more spiritual.

403
00:35:47,000 --> 00:35:50,000
Now let's look at the typical hero in the East and West.

404
00:35:50,000 --> 00:35:58,000
A Western hero wants to change the world to make it better for himself and those around him, while an Eastern hero wants to change himself.

405
00:35:58,000 --> 00:36:10,000
Western superheroes fight evil to restore justice, peace, correct the incorrect, while Asian heroes either accept their fate or retreat to a forest for some contemplation.

406
00:36:10,000 --> 00:36:16,000
Jesus perhaps the greatest Western hero confronted injustice and paid for it with his own life.

407
00:36:16,000 --> 00:36:20,000
A sacrifice you can see manifests in Harry Potter as well.

408
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:24,000
The Buddha, the founder of Buddhism, however, went to the forest to change himself.

409
00:36:24,000 --> 00:36:27,000
Lao Tzu, the founder of Taoism, retreated the mountains.

410
00:36:27,000 --> 00:36:32,000
In other words, Western philosophy is about change while Eastern philosophy is more about accepting your fate.

411
00:36:32,000 --> 00:36:39,000
A great example of this in literature can be seen in the novels of the Japanese British Nobel Prize-winning author Kazuo Shiguro.

412
00:36:39,000 --> 00:36:44,000
His characters obey their fate and rarely question their somewhat unfair circumstances.

413
00:36:44,000 --> 00:36:49,000
However, a typical hero in the West would rebel against their circumstance to change the world.

414
00:36:49,000 --> 00:36:59,000
Accepting one's fate or putting up with an unfavorable environment is seen as a sign of weakness in the West, while those same traits are seen as a sign of strength in the East.

415
00:36:59,000 --> 00:37:03,000
By the East, my focus is mainly Old India, China and Japan.

416
00:37:03,000 --> 00:37:09,000
So a Western hero wants to change the world while an Eastern hero wants to change himself to adapt.

417
00:37:09,000 --> 00:37:17,000
In today's world, East and West have come together a lot because Western mode of production, i.e. capitalism, has taken over the world.

