01:15:07,000 --> 01:15:13,000
If we have a big house, next time we will not be fulfilled if we don't get an even bigger house.

811
01:15:13,000 --> 01:15:18,000
Bigger cars, more partners, more wealth, friends, subscribers, followers.

812
01:15:18,000 --> 01:15:22,000
At no point in our life we can satisfactorily say it is enough.

813
01:15:22,000 --> 01:15:24,000
A good example is addiction.

814
01:15:24,000 --> 01:15:31,000
If a small dose makes you high today, but you need a larger dose to give you the same high a month later or a year later.

815
01:15:31,000 --> 01:15:35,000
In other words, as you experience more, your desires also grow bigger.

816
01:15:35,000 --> 01:15:41,000
So life is just an endless cycle of desire, fulfillment of that desire and more desires.

817
01:15:41,000 --> 01:15:43,000
How do we solve this problem?

818
01:15:43,000 --> 01:15:50,000
To ease suffering, according to Buddhism, we should nip our wants and the bad by detaching ourselves from our desires.

819
01:15:51,000 --> 01:15:55,000
Don't chase things and be happy in the moment.

820
01:15:55,000 --> 01:15:57,000
But it's easier said than done.

821
01:15:57,000 --> 01:16:01,000
Everyone says it's a good idea to be content with what you have right now.

822
01:16:01,000 --> 01:16:03,000
But curbing your desire is not an easy job.

823
01:16:03,000 --> 01:16:04,000
Why is it so hard?

824
01:16:04,000 --> 01:16:08,000
Here's when Buddhism gets really interesting and profoundly deep.

825
01:16:08,000 --> 01:16:10,000
We all think we are who we are.

826
01:16:10,000 --> 01:16:13,000
We have a sense of the self we call me and you.

827
01:16:13,000 --> 01:16:15,000
We think it's somewhat solid entity.

828
01:16:15,000 --> 01:16:19,000
And what's in religions, this self is imparted to us from God.

829
01:16:19,000 --> 01:16:20,000
It's real.

830
01:16:20,000 --> 01:16:24,000
This individual self is genuine and for the most part unchangeable.

831
01:16:24,000 --> 01:16:27,000
According to Buddhism, however, you are wrong.

832
01:16:27,000 --> 01:16:28,000
Why?

833
01:16:28,000 --> 01:16:30,000
The self or ego is not real.

834
01:16:30,000 --> 01:16:35,000
It's just an illusion or mirage or a temporary imposter attached to your body.

835
01:16:35,000 --> 01:16:38,000
You could say like a parasite, it lives on you.

836
01:16:38,000 --> 01:16:40,000
What does it do inside us?

837
01:16:40,000 --> 01:16:44,000
This imposter self fuels our desires, ambitions and goals.

838
01:16:44,000 --> 01:16:48,000
In other words, it uses us to go out in the world and achieve things.

839
01:16:48,000 --> 01:16:51,000
But at the end of the day, we still don't feel fulfilled.

840
01:16:51,000 --> 01:16:54,000
Especially when we achieve everything and death hits us.

841
01:16:54,000 --> 01:16:55,000
We lose our shit.

842
01:16:55,000 --> 01:16:59,000
Because we went through so much trouble acquiring our wealth, fame, power,

843
01:16:59,000 --> 01:17:02,000
and now death is snatching all away from us.

844
01:17:02,000 --> 01:17:03,000
It's a bad deal.

845
01:17:03,000 --> 01:17:05,000
So what is the solution, Mr. Buddha?

846
01:17:05,000 --> 01:17:07,000
His answer might shock you.

847
01:17:07,000 --> 01:17:10,000
According to Buddhism, to be truly enlightened and blissful,

848
01:17:10,000 --> 01:17:13,000
you have to achieve the Nirvana stage.

849
01:17:13,000 --> 01:17:16,000
Which means we must kill the imposter self.

850
01:17:16,000 --> 01:17:20,000
This thing we call the self or ego is the source of all our desires.

851
01:17:20,000 --> 01:17:23,000
To not desire anything, we must remove the self.

852
01:17:23,000 --> 01:17:26,000
According to Buddhism, our soul is the real thing,

853
01:17:26,000 --> 01:17:28,000
and also very much universal,

854
01:17:28,000 --> 01:17:31,000
while the self is a kind of picture we put in our head

855
01:17:31,000 --> 01:17:35,000
every time we are born in our various reincarnations.

856
01:17:35,000 --> 01:17:38,000
One way to understand this is perhaps through Mr. Plato,

857
01:17:38,000 --> 01:17:41,000
who also said that the idea of things is the perfect form

858
01:17:41,000 --> 01:17:44,000
and real things on the outside is a mere shadow of the real thing.

859
01:17:44,000 --> 01:17:47,000
In Buddhism, your soul is genuine, eternal, and universal,

860
01:17:47,000 --> 01:17:50,000
while your body or ego are temporary and fleeting.

861
01:17:50,000 --> 01:17:54,000
We are not separate from the universe, but a tiny part of a big hole.

862
01:17:54,000 --> 01:17:56,000
To become happy and one with the universe,

863
01:17:56,000 --> 01:17:59,000
you must detach yourself from your desires and kill the self

864
01:17:59,000 --> 01:18:04,000
through meditation, solitude, and rigorous physical and mental discipline.

865
01:18:04,000 --> 01:18:07,000
A discipline mind brings happiness.

866
01:18:07,000 --> 01:18:10,000
This is very similar to Arthur Schopenhauer's philosophy

867
01:18:10,000 --> 01:18:14,000
of the blind universal will, which is a force beyond our control,

868
01:18:14,000 --> 01:18:16,000
yet it rules most of what we do in life.

869
01:18:16,000 --> 01:18:20,000
There's a disagreement whether Schopenhauer reached the same conclusion

870
01:18:20,000 --> 01:18:22,000
independent of Buddhism or Hinduism,

871
01:18:22,000 --> 01:18:25,000
or he was influenced by these Indian philosophies.

872
01:18:25,000 --> 01:18:28,000
I'll discuss Schopenhauer's philosophy in more detail later on.

873
01:18:28,000 --> 01:18:32,000
So according to Buddhism, to be truly enlightened is to not see yourself

874
01:18:32,000 --> 01:18:36,000
as a separate self, but part of a bigger whole, part of conscious universe.

875
01:18:36,000 --> 01:18:41,000
So true inner peace comes not from outside, for example, by achieving your goals,

876
01:18:41,000 --> 01:18:44,000
but from inside once you become enlightened.

877
01:18:44,000 --> 01:18:47,000
Buddha's teachings through various forms of Buddhism

878
01:18:47,000 --> 01:18:50,000
are incredibly important in most of East Asia.

879
01:18:50,000 --> 01:18:54,000
Buddhism has also become one of the most influential philosophies in the West too,

880
01:18:54,000 --> 01:18:59,000
as it emphasizes individual inner journey rather than collective prayers in a church.

881
01:18:59,000 --> 01:19:02,000
So to sum up, Buddha was a rich, powerful prince,

882
01:19:02,000 --> 01:19:08,000
but wasn't fulfilled in life and realized that all humans suffer because of our desires.

883
01:19:08,000 --> 01:19:11,000
To ease suffering we should detach ourselves from our desires

884
01:19:11,000 --> 01:19:17,000
and to be truly blissful we should eliminate the self or ego through meditation and mental discipline.

885
01:19:19,000 --> 01:19:20,000
Confucius.

886
01:19:20,000 --> 01:19:26,000
While both Lausi and the Buddha escaped society for some solitude and inner peace,

887
01:19:26,000 --> 01:19:30,000
Confucius, who lived between 551 and 479 BCE,

888
01:19:30,000 --> 01:19:34,000
however, tried to solve the practical socio-political questions

889
01:19:34,000 --> 01:19:38,000
like how we can live politically and socially together in peace and harmony

890
01:19:38,000 --> 01:19:41,000
or how to organize society in a way that is peaceful.

891
01:19:41,000 --> 01:19:46,000
So his philosophy is less individualistic but more concerned about the collective existence,

892
01:19:46,000 --> 01:19:49,000
especially in big cities and countries.

893
01:19:49,000 --> 01:19:53,000
To find a great solution for socio-political coexistence,

894
01:19:53,000 --> 01:19:58,000
Confucius looked at how nature organizes things, especially in the animal kingdom.

895
01:19:58,000 --> 01:20:03,000
One of the biggest problems and the main source of wars and violence in human society

896
01:20:03,000 --> 01:20:10,000
is when there is confusion as to who stands where, who gets what, who owns what, who is responsible for what.

897
01:20:10,000 --> 01:20:16,000
He understood that the best method was the natural hierarchy or a pyramid social system.

898
01:20:16,000 --> 01:20:21,000
Without an established system of hierarchy or authority, there is chaos and confusion.

899
01:20:21,000 --> 01:20:26,000
And hierarchy allows everyone to know their place, so there is no confusion

900
01:20:26,000 --> 01:20:29,000
or conflict as to which chair belongs to who.

901
01:20:29,000 --> 01:20:35,000
Removing social confusion was Confucius' main task, pun intended.

902
01:20:35,000 --> 01:20:40,000
Now, not only everyone knows their own place, they also know other people's places too.

903
01:20:40,000 --> 01:20:45,000
So instead of a police watching everyone or patrolling the whole society,

904
01:20:45,000 --> 01:20:47,000
now everyone can watch each other.

905
01:20:47,000 --> 01:20:52,000
If someone sits in the wrong chair, other people can tell him it is not his seat.

906
01:20:52,000 --> 01:20:59,000
So if everyone knows their place, everyone can watch, everyone, so nobody dares to disrupt the social harmony.

907
01:20:59,000 --> 01:21:04,000
So kings at the top of the pyramid and everyone else take their place based on their ranks and age,

908
01:21:04,000 --> 01:21:06,000
just like a game of chess.

909
01:21:06,000 --> 01:21:09,000
Perhaps the most logical game humans have invented.

910
01:21:09,000 --> 01:21:16,000
Confucius also realized that everything starts in the family, because it's the first line of defense against chaos.

911
01:21:16,000 --> 01:21:20,000
A solid family structure means a solid foundation for society.

912
01:21:20,000 --> 01:21:25,000
Inside the family, the man is at the top, then wife, then sons, and then daughters.

913
01:21:25,000 --> 01:21:30,000
One of the most common criticism against Confucius is the possibility of tyranny.

914
01:21:30,000 --> 01:21:32,000
Those in positions of power can abuse it.

915
01:21:32,000 --> 01:21:36,000
Confucius also emphasized responsibility and duty.

916
01:21:36,000 --> 01:21:40,000
Those at the top are responsible to protect those below them.

917
01:21:40,000 --> 01:21:47,000
A king is responsible to keep people safe and a man in the family is responsible to protect and provide for his wife and children.

918
01:21:47,000 --> 01:21:52,000
Those below in return are loyal and follow their superiors and do as asked.

919
01:21:52,000 --> 01:21:59,000
To understand Confucianism, you should look things not just from an individual point of view, but from a collective perspective.

920
01:21:59,000 --> 01:22:05,000
For example, if your body parts didn't function in alignment with the rest of your body, you are sick and needs treatment.

921
01:22:05,000 --> 01:22:06,000
Society is the same.

922
01:22:06,000 --> 01:22:12,000
If one or few members push things in the opposite direction, there's violence, which is a social illness.

923
01:22:12,000 --> 01:22:21,000
You might think it's pretty outdated, but you would be surprised that this Confucian hierarchy is pretty efficient system, which is at work in modern companies.

924
01:22:21,000 --> 01:22:27,000
Because we hear this cliche that no work is done by a committee, which is true in most situations.

925
01:22:27,000 --> 01:22:32,000
Most corporate structures follow a strict and rigid hierarchy and a chain of command.

926
01:22:32,000 --> 01:22:36,000
In the animal kingdom, a hierarchy is often achieved through violence.

927
01:22:36,000 --> 01:22:41,000
But Confucian says, since it's natural, we might as well adopt it to reduce violence.

928
01:22:41,000 --> 01:22:45,000
Of course, in the modern age, revolutions are a common occurrence.

929
01:22:45,000 --> 01:22:48,000
Those at the bottom rebel against the establishment.

930
01:22:48,000 --> 01:22:52,000
That's why Confucius emphasized duty and responsibility.

931
01:22:52,000 --> 01:22:55,000
When a ruler becomes tyrannical, he fails his duty.

932
01:22:55,000 --> 01:22:59,000
It all comes down to respecting your role in society.

933
01:22:59,000 --> 01:23:04,000
Quote, without feelings of respect, what is there to distinguish men from beasts?

934
01:23:04,000 --> 01:23:17,000
Today, China, Korea and Japan have adopted these Confucian methods in sorting out social situations where seniority and juniority plays a major role in schools, universities and companies.

935
01:23:17,000 --> 01:23:22,000
Loyalty and respect are significant in Confucianism, but also meritocracy.

936
01:23:22,000 --> 01:23:28,000
As a result, traditionally, China had a strict civil service examination for centuries,

937
01:23:28,000 --> 01:23:33,000
and only the very bright and intelligent were recruited for high military and government jobs.

938
01:23:33,000 --> 01:23:37,000
In the 20th century, however, Mao Zedong, the egalitarian socialist,

939
01:23:37,000 --> 01:23:41,000
tried to dismantle the Confucian class hierarchy through the Cultural Revolution.

940
01:23:41,000 --> 01:23:44,000
That caused great pain for a lot of people.

941
01:23:44,000 --> 01:23:50,000
But of course, the Chinese Communist Party replaced the old class-based Confucian hierarchy with a political hierarchy.

942
01:23:50,000 --> 01:24:00,000
Many economists attribute China's rapid economic development to this efficient hierarchical system as China was run like a company, the president being the CEO of China.

943
01:24:00,000 --> 01:24:05,000
Things get done quickly, but of course, it also comes at a cost of many voices being suppressed.

944
01:24:05,000 --> 01:24:11,000
Traditionally, the Chinese Communist Party used to distance itself from the archaic Confucius philosophy

945
01:24:11,000 --> 01:24:19,000
because it contradicts the egalitarian philosophy of socialism in which everyone is equal and there is no hierarchy at least on paper.

946
01:24:19,000 --> 01:24:22,000
But in reality, every human society has been hierarchical.

947
01:24:22,000 --> 01:24:26,000
Even today, China is slowly moving towards a more Confucian philosophy.

948
01:24:26,000 --> 01:24:31,000
As China is developing, not only it's utilizing a Confucian hierarchy for its efficiency,

949
01:24:31,000 --> 01:24:40,000
but it's also cultivating a more robust culture of meritocracy and traditional masculinity which were centered on Confucian philosophy.

950
01:24:40,000 --> 01:24:47,000
To sum up, Laozi's teaching is not to resist or destroy or go against nature, but to flow with nature.

951
01:24:47,000 --> 01:24:51,000
As a result, he says we should be more intuitive and spontaneous.

952
01:24:51,000 --> 01:24:57,000
In other words, humans are of nature, so it's time we forget our humanness and live in the flow of nature.

953
01:24:57,000 --> 01:25:03,000
The Buddha taught that suffering is universal because of our goals, desires and ambitions.

954
01:25:03,000 --> 01:25:07,000
To find true peace is to look inside, not outside material success.

955
01:25:07,000 --> 01:25:13,000
And to be truly happy is to kill your ego or the self that has ambition and desires.

956
01:25:13,000 --> 01:25:22,000
Confucius tackled the sociopolitical question of how to live a peaceful coexistence through a hierarchical system in which everyone knows the place and position in society.

957
01:25:22,000 --> 01:25:28,000
While the Greeks were questioning truth, authority, poking holes at the natural world to understand its property,

958
01:25:28,000 --> 01:25:35,000
those in the east were seeking a harmonious life with nature, not only with other humans, but with all creatures on earth.

959
01:25:35,000 --> 01:25:42,000
The Greeks disagreed with each other while the Asians tried to find agreement, consents us, not only among humans,

960
01:25:42,000 --> 01:25:45,000
but also between humans and the natural world.

961
01:25:45,000 --> 01:25:54,000
The fact these three figures founded a religion of their own while the three Greeks did not show the fundamental difference between eastern and western philosophy.

962
01:25:54,000 --> 01:26:00,000
And the east societies are generally more group centered, while in the west it's more individual centered.

963
01:26:00,000 --> 01:26:06,000
But if you really think about it, the philosophies of these three eastern thinkers is highly individualized.

964
01:26:06,000 --> 01:26:11,000
They put the emphasis on the individual to take charge of themselves.

965
01:26:11,000 --> 01:26:14,000
Don't change the world, change yourself.

966
01:26:14,000 --> 01:26:24,000
So while eastern social fabric is communitarian, the philosophies are individualistic as they put demand on the individual to take responsibility for changing themselves.

967
01:26:24,000 --> 01:26:27,000
So they adapt to the society they live in.

968
01:26:27,000 --> 01:26:29,000
Don't change others, but yourself.

969
01:26:29,000 --> 01:26:32,000
Don't change nature, but yourself.

970
01:26:32,000 --> 01:26:37,000
The Greeks however focused on how to change nature as quickly, efficiently as possible.

971
01:26:37,000 --> 01:26:43,000
So in the west individuality is static, God-given or born, while social fabric is dynamic.

972
01:26:43,000 --> 01:26:50,000
In other words, in western philosophy the individual is solid and the society and nature malleable and changeable.

973
01:26:50,000 --> 01:26:56,000
In the east however, nature is as well as society's fabrics are static while the individual is changeable.

974
01:26:56,000 --> 01:27:01,000
In other words, do not attempt to change others or nature because it's easier to change yourself.

975
01:27:01,000 --> 01:27:06,000
If you cannot fit in with others, take a good look at yourself and find what's wrong with you.

976
01:27:06,000 --> 01:27:11,000
People in the east are less likely to complain about the world instead try to adapt to the world.

977
01:27:11,000 --> 01:27:16,000
Before you complain that I'm generalizing too much, sit back and relax and look at yourself in the mirror.

978
01:27:16,000 --> 01:27:18,000
Don't worry, I'm kidding.

979
01:27:18,000 --> 01:27:21,000
Next I'll discuss two distinct approaches to philosophy.

980
01:27:21,000 --> 01:27:27,000
Animalism that sees humans as animals therefore needed to be herded to bring order.

981
01:27:27,000 --> 01:27:31,000
And humanism that sees all humans as equal to one another.

982
01:27:31,000 --> 01:27:38,000
In other words, elitism versus egalitarianism or carnivorous versus herbivorous philosophies.

983
01:27:42,000 --> 01:27:53,000
Previously I discussed eastern philosophy versus western philosophy and how one employed rationality to tame nature while the other employed spirituality to tame the individual.

984
01:27:53,000 --> 01:27:59,000
Today I'll look at two core philosophical schools, humanism versus animalism.

985
01:27:59,000 --> 01:28:04,000
Humanism is a belief that humans are somewhat special either created by God or not.

986
01:28:04,000 --> 01:28:09,000
Therefore the purpose of any society is to protect all humans equally.

987
01:28:09,000 --> 01:28:19,000
Humanism is also called egalitarianism with a few babies of its own like socialism, feminism, liberalism and postmodernism.

988
01:28:19,000 --> 01:28:25,000
Elitism or animalism on the other hand is a belief that some humans are more equal than others.

989
01:28:25,000 --> 01:28:31,000
Especially the rulers, kings, elite class of people or the talented people as in meritocracy.

990
01:28:31,000 --> 01:28:35,000
This is because hierarchy is very much part of the animal kingdom.

991
01:28:35,000 --> 01:28:37,000
The strongest wins the race.

992
01:28:37,000 --> 01:28:43,000
But as human civilization has progressed and we have become more efficient and taming nature,

993
01:28:43,000 --> 01:28:48,000
the historical trend is moving towards a more egalitarian human society.

994
01:28:48,000 --> 01:28:54,000
So here's the most important question, was Karl Marx right that the future is communism?

995
01:28:54,000 --> 01:28:59,000
But first let me explain the history of these two divergent philosophical approaches.

996
01:28:59,000 --> 01:29:03,000
And it used some of the most important philosophers on each side.

997
01:29:03,000 --> 01:29:07,000
Humanism has its roots in religions and the West Christianity and Judaism

998
01:29:07,000 --> 01:29:12,000
at its core believed that all humans beings were equal in the eye of God.

999
01:29:12,000 --> 01:29:17,000
Augustine of Hippo believed all humans have free will to choose between good and evil.

1000
01:29:17,000 --> 01:29:20,000
He also said that one should love everyone equally.

1001
01:29:20,000 --> 01:29:24,000
Quote, the measure of love is to love without measure.

1002
01:29:24,000 --> 01:29:30,000
Thomas Aquinas, another Christian philosopher, argued that God created the world and all humans were equal,

1003
01:29:30,000 --> 01:29:32,000
especially in freedom.

1004
01:29:32,000 --> 01:29:37,000
Quote, by nature all men are equal in liberty but not in other endowments.

1005
01:29:37,000 --> 01:29:43,000
Outside the religious tradition the first true humanist might be Mosey who lived in the 4th century BC in China.

1006
01:29:43,000 --> 01:29:46,000
He advocated a kind of universal humanism.

1007
01:29:46,000 --> 01:29:53,000
At the time Confucianism was the dominant philosophy in China in which society was divided based on ranks and hierarchies.

1008
01:29:53,000 --> 01:29:57,000
So Mosey believed in universal reciprocation.

1009
01:29:57,000 --> 01:30:01,000
Quote, universal love is really the way of the sage kings.

1010
01:30:01,000 --> 01:30:05,000
It is what gives peace to the rulers and sustenance to the people.

1011
01:30:05,000 --> 01:30:08,000
This is an early form of humanism.

1012
01:30:08,000 --> 01:30:15,000
Another early figure was a 6th century Persian philosopher Mazdat who promoted economic equality among all people.

1013
01:30:15,000 --> 01:30:20,000
He even protested against the rich having many wives while the poor having no wife.

1014
01:30:20,000 --> 01:30:25,000
His idea became quite influential in the Persian Empire but soon fizzled out.

1015
01:30:25,000 --> 01:30:32,000
On the opposite of humanism we have the school of elitist philosophy which we can term as realism as called in politics.

1016
01:30:32,000 --> 01:30:39,000
The basic idea of realism is that humans are chaotic and erratic animals that need to be tamed and controlled and ruled,

1017
01:30:39,000 --> 01:30:44,000
not through honesty or fairness but through deception or brute force.

1018
01:30:46,000 --> 01:30:54,000
One of the earliest realist philosophers was San Tzu who lived in China between 544 and 496 BCE.

1019
01:30:54,000 --> 01:31:04,000
In his famous book The Art of War he employs nature's tactics such as camouflage, deception and even submission to survive or dominate others, especially in wars.

1020
01:31:04,000 --> 01:31:07,000
His philosophy was to win at all costs so to speak.

1021
01:31:07,000 --> 01:31:14,000
For him life is not about fairness or equality, it was about winning which is at the heart of evolutionary biology.

1022
01:31:14,000 --> 01:31:19,000
You only survive or thrive if you win nature's battle and overcome hurdles.

1023
01:31:19,000 --> 01:31:24,000
Some of his strategies in The Art of War are socially counterintuitive like this.

1024
01:31:24,000 --> 01:31:31,000
Like he says you must appear small when you're big and appear big when you're small in order to deceive your enemy.

1025
01:31:31,000 --> 01:31:35,000
In San Tzu's Art of War honesty is the worst policy.

1026
01:31:35,000 --> 01:31:42,000
Quote when the enemy is relaxed make them toil, when full starve them, when settled make them move.

1027
01:31:42,000 --> 01:31:46,000
In other words, stand tall when you're small and sit small when you're tall.

1028
01:31:46,000 --> 01:31:53,000
These are some basic survival tactics in the wild, for example in the battle between the carnivores and herbivores.

1029
01:31:53,000 --> 01:31:58,000
A gazelle jumps higher to show it's health so that cheetahs don't bother chasing them.

1030
01:31:58,000 --> 01:32:07,000
Some of the tactics are also to throw off your enemy like when negotiating ask for less when you want more, which is still in use in corporate capitalism.

1031
01:32:07,000 --> 01:32:15,000
The Art of War's basic rules are to know yourself, your enemy and your environment, time your attack and truths.

1032
01:32:15,000 --> 01:32:19,000
While at the same time make sure your enemy knows nothing truthful about you.

1033
01:32:19,000 --> 01:32:23,000
Be a peacock when small and be a mouse when big.

1034
01:32:23,000 --> 01:32:29,000
So this is the earliest form of political deception in order to prolong your rule over others.

1035
01:32:29,000 --> 01:32:32,000
The winners are those who lie the best.

1036
01:32:32,000 --> 01:32:38,000
So Sansu borrowed his philosophy from the animal kingdom where there is no morality, only winners.

1037
01:32:40,000 --> 01:32:48,000
Machiavelli who lived between 1469 and 1527 was an Italian thinker who is famous for his book The Prince,

1038
01:32:48,000 --> 01:32:58,000
in which he advises the rulers to use any methods available to them to achieve the goal of maximizing their power and domination over other humans.

1039
01:32:58,000 --> 01:33:07,000
In other words, the famous line that the end justifies the means which goes contrary to the humanist and religious morality of protecting life.

1040
01:33:07,000 --> 01:33:11,000
Put, it's better to be feared than loved if you cannot be both.

1041
01:33:11,000 --> 01:33:17,000
He argued that a ruler must be like a savage lion when needed and a cunning fox when needed.

1042
01:33:17,000 --> 01:33:23,000
So brute force combined with cunning deceptions are needed in order to rule over society.

1043
01:33:23,000 --> 01:33:33,000
Why? Because humans are savages and they are waiting for your weakest moment to strike and take away your power like Hamlet's uncle and Shakespeare's play Hamlet.

1044
01:33:33,000 --> 01:33:42,000
Machiavelli lived a few centuries before Darwin's theory of evolution by natural selection, but he still understood the savage nature of human politics.

1045
01:33:42,000 --> 01:33:47,000
In other words, moralities for the weak and power and deception are for the strong.

1046
01:33:48,000 --> 01:33:52,000
Quote, he who wishes to be obeyed must know how to command.

1047
01:33:52,000 --> 01:33:59,000
In order to prevent a rebellion, a ruler must show terror and fear for its subject to behave well.

1048
01:33:59,000 --> 01:34:06,000
Those at the top of society have the most to lose so they can use any means available to them to make sure they keep their power and wealth.

1049
01:34:06,000 --> 01:34:12,000
They use the police, the legal system and whatever else so nobody can take those things away from them.

1050
01:34:12,000 --> 01:34:16,000
So, just like Sansu, Machiavelli based his philosophy on the animal kingdom.

1051
01:34:16,000 --> 01:34:20,000
It's not about equality or fairness, it's about winning and conquering.

1052
01:34:22,000 --> 01:34:28,000
Thomas Hobbes was an English philosopher who lived between 1588 and 1679.

1053
01:34:28,000 --> 01:34:36,000
In his book, Leviathan, he argued that humans are savages and only a civilized state can protect humans from each other.

1054
01:34:36,000 --> 01:34:41,000
In other words, humans have established states to escape the brutality of nature.

1055
01:34:41,000 --> 01:34:45,000
According to him, humans are physical machines and nature.

1056
01:34:45,000 --> 01:34:51,000
But when entering society, they gave up their savage tendencies and power to live peacefully.

1057
01:34:51,000 --> 01:34:58,000
Quote, life in the state of nature is solitary, poor, nasty, brutish and short.

1058
01:34:58,000 --> 01:35:00,000
Fear of violence is always there.

1059
01:35:00,000 --> 01:35:06,000
To escape it, humans have made a contract with their governing rulers and returned for their obedience and freedom.

1060
01:35:06,000 --> 01:35:11,000
The state provides them with peace, justice, protection for them and their property.

1061
01:35:11,000 --> 01:35:16,000
Just like Machiavelli, Hobbes believed in the use of force to tame people.

1062
01:35:16,000 --> 01:35:21,000
Quote, not believing in force is the same as not believing in gravitation.

1063
01:35:21,000 --> 01:35:27,000
Despite his argument for a civilized state, he understood that humans were an essence savage animal.

1064
01:35:27,000 --> 01:35:32,000
So, Sansu drew on the animal kingdom saying deception was better than honesty.

1065
01:35:32,000 --> 01:35:39,000
Machiavelli went even further saying that deception combined with brute force are justified to tame humans.

1066
01:35:39,000 --> 01:35:44,000
Hobbes argued a civilized state has every right to tame the unruly humans.

1067
01:35:44,000 --> 01:35:50,000
Now, let's look at a few philosophers who oppose this animalistic philosophy based on the natural world.

1068
01:35:50,000 --> 01:35:54,000
These philosophers saw human life as somewhat sacred.

1069
01:35:55,000 --> 01:36:05,000
Voltaire who lived between 1694 and 1777 was a French philosopher who believed in a kind of universal individual liberty.

1070
01:36:05,000 --> 01:36:07,000
Not tyranny as Machiavelli suggested.

1071
01:36:07,000 --> 01:36:13,000
Unlike Machiavelli's iron rule, he believed in open skepticism and freedom of expression for all

1072
01:36:13,000 --> 01:36:19,000
so anyone could criticize and even rebel against the dominant traditions and dogmas.

1073
01:36:19,000 --> 01:36:24,000
Quote, men are equal, it's not birth, but virtue that makes the difference.

1074
01:36:24,000 --> 01:36:32,000
In other words, he didn't support the idea that the rulers and kings had a birthright authority over truth or liberty.

1075
01:36:32,000 --> 01:36:35,000
The church or the state should not hold absolute power.

1076
01:36:35,000 --> 01:36:42,000
Instead, everyone, despite their socioeconomic status, deserves the right to have an education and access to knowledge.

1077
01:36:42,000 --> 01:36:48,000
Today, liberal democracies in the West follow the principles of free speech and individual autonomy.

1078
01:36:48,000 --> 01:36:51,000
Ideas that were promoted by Voltaire.

1079
01:36:51,000 --> 01:36:55,000
So he's often considered the father of liberal individualism.

1080
01:36:55,000 --> 01:37:01,000
Because he believed everyone, irrespective of their socioeconomic class, deserved to be equally free.

1081
01:37:01,000 --> 01:37:09,000
So nature works with hierarchy, but Voltaire argued that every human deserves equal freedom to express themselves.

1082
01:37:10,000 --> 01:37:16,000
Jean-Jacques Rousseau who lived between 1712 and 1778 was born in Geneva.

1083
01:37:16,000 --> 01:37:21,000
Unlike Thomas Hobbes who said man is born savage but tamed in society,

1084
01:37:21,000 --> 01:37:28,000
Rousseau believed that humans are naturally good but they are contaminated or tainted in society to act terrible.

1085
01:37:28,000 --> 01:37:33,000
He famously said, man is born free yet he is everywhere in chains.

1086
01:37:33,000 --> 01:37:37,000
This was especially true in big cities where people turned selfish.

1087
01:37:37,000 --> 01:37:42,000
He believed in the country people were naturally nicer, friendlier and fairer

1088
01:37:42,000 --> 01:37:50,000
but once people migrated to the cities instead of becoming more civilized, ironically they turned into selfish animals.

1089
01:37:50,000 --> 01:37:55,000
Unlike Hobbes' top-down approach, Rousseau believed in a bottom-up approach

1090
01:37:55,000 --> 01:38:01,000
arguing that the masses should be able to run the state, not some select individuals like kings and generals.

1091
01:38:01,000 --> 01:38:07,000
His famous book The Social Contract is said to have influenced the French Revolution in 1789

1092
01:38:07,000 --> 01:38:13,000
in which the anti-monarchy revolutionaries toppled the king and France became a republic.

1093
01:38:13,000 --> 01:38:19,000
Of course it didn't last very long but it sowed the seed of freedom, equality and brotherhood

1094
01:38:19,000 --> 01:38:25,000
which resulted in three major ideologies of socialism, liberalism and nationalism

1095
01:38:25,000 --> 01:38:29,000
which have dominated politics for centuries ever since.

1096
01:38:29,000 --> 01:38:34,000
So Rousseau's egalitarian approach had a huge influence in political history.

1097
01:38:35,000 --> 01:38:42,000
So to sum up, the humanists argued that since life is too short let's all be more equal, fairer and nicer to each other.

1098
01:38:42,000 --> 01:38:48,000
Mosey argued for an equal universal education, Rousseau for equal political participation

1099
01:38:48,000 --> 01:38:52,000
and Voltaire for equal freedom for everyone to express himself.

1100
01:38:52,000 --> 01:38:57,000
Political animalists or elitists on the other hand argued that since life is too short

1101
01:38:57,000 --> 01:39:01,000
it's all about winning, conquering and dominating others.

1102
01:39:01,000 --> 01:39:05,000
So they don't trust all humans therefore promoted a more robust political regime

1103
01:39:05,000 --> 01:39:09,000
that didn't allow people to be free to challenge the ruler or the state.

1104
01:39:09,000 --> 01:39:17,000
Sansou used deception, Machiavelli justified repression and Hobbes promoted its state as a tool to control human savages.

1105
01:39:17,000 --> 01:39:24,000
Now as a historical trend we are moving towards an egalitarian humanist future at least in principle.

1106
01:39:24,000 --> 01:39:30,000
Also this was Karl Marx's prediction that slowly we are heading towards a communist utopia.

1107
01:39:30,000 --> 01:39:34,000
In reality however all human societies are highly unequal and hierarchical

1108
01:39:34,000 --> 01:39:38,000
and it's unlikely that this will change for a foreseeable future.

1109
01:39:38,000 --> 01:39:45,000
Humanism invented by humans while elitism or animalism invented by nature and evolutionary biology

1110
01:39:45,000 --> 01:39:51,000
were all born unequal in beauty, talent, intellect and physical strength

1111
01:39:51,000 --> 01:39:57,000
which contribute to societies being dominated by those who are naturally blessed either with talent or beauty.

1112
01:39:57,000 --> 01:40:01,000
But despite nature not being helpful in producing us equally

1113
01:40:01,000 --> 01:40:06,000
there is a deep desire among humans for equality, fairness and justice.

1114
01:40:06,000 --> 01:40:10,000
You could say that humankind is called kind for a reason.

1115
01:40:10,000 --> 01:40:15,000
As human civilization has improved and the more we have tame nature

1116
01:40:15,000 --> 01:40:19,000
we have become more confident that a humanist utopia is possible.

1117
01:40:19,000 --> 01:40:24,000
So in recent centuries egalitarian philosophy has become more dominant

1118
01:40:24,000 --> 01:40:28,000
which a few centuries back must have been unthinkable.

1119
01:40:28,000 --> 01:40:32,000
Socialist experiments showed the failure of egalitarianism in Russia

1120
01:40:32,000 --> 01:40:35,000
but the idea is still pretty strong in the world.

1121
01:40:35,000 --> 01:40:42,000
Who knows in the future humans might produce human babies in labs who are identical in all attributes

1122
01:40:42,000 --> 01:40:45,000
to create a truly egalitarian utopia.

1123
01:40:45,000 --> 01:40:51,000
Once you produce baby outside the natural process equality is a lot easier to achieve.

1124
01:40:51,000 --> 01:40:56,000
Identical babies produce identical adults, a brave new world kind of world.

1125
01:40:56,000 --> 01:40:58,000
But will we be happy?

1126
01:40:58,000 --> 01:41:03,000
Next I'll discuss the battle between pursuing knowledge and pursuing happiness.

1127
01:41:03,000 --> 01:41:06,000
In other words those who pursue knowledge to gain power

1128
01:41:06,000 --> 01:41:10,000
and those who pursue happiness and peace to live a simpler life.

1129
01:41:14,000 --> 01:41:18,000
Previously I discussed the two philosophical approaches to organizing society

1130
01:41:18,000 --> 01:41:21,000
egalitarian humanism versus hierarchical elitism.

1131
01:41:21,000 --> 01:41:24,000
Here I'll discuss fundamental question about the meaning of life.

1132
01:41:24,000 --> 01:41:27,000
Are we here to know the world or be happy?

1133
01:41:27,000 --> 01:41:30,000
Are we here to seek knowledge or happiness?

1134
01:41:30,000 --> 01:41:33,000
So in this segment I'll look at a few important philosophers.

1135
01:41:33,000 --> 01:41:39,000
On the knowledge side I'll look at the philosophy of Francis Bacon, Martin Heidegger and Michel Foucault.

1136
01:41:39,000 --> 01:41:45,000
On the happiness side I'll look at the philosophy of Erasmus, Michel Montaigne and Bertrand Russell.

1137
01:41:45,000 --> 01:41:49,000
As I discussed earlier, philosophy is concerned mainly with two questions.

1138
01:41:49,000 --> 01:41:54,000
Ontology asks what is out there and epistemology asks how we know it.

1139
01:41:54,000 --> 01:41:56,000
So knowledge is fundamental to philosophy.

1140
01:41:56,000 --> 01:42:02,000
You could say we humans are hardwired to see, understand, analyze and interpret the world.

1141
01:42:02,000 --> 01:42:09,000
And in other words we are curious creatures so the development of modern science is just the byproduct of this curiosity.

1142
01:42:09,000 --> 01:42:13,000
And our thirst for knowledge drives innovation and social change.

1143
01:42:13,000 --> 01:42:16,000
But we are also creatures who seek happiness.

1144
01:42:16,000 --> 01:42:20,000
While knowledge can empower us, it doesn't make us happy.

1145
01:42:20,000 --> 01:42:26,000
While knowledge can transform our lives, it doesn't guarantee happiness or peace of mind.

1146
01:42:26,000 --> 01:42:31,000
As I discussed earlier, the first philosopher to methodically seek the truth was Socrates.

1147
01:42:31,000 --> 01:42:37,000
And later Aristotle improved it by giving the approach of scientific and empirical tinge to it.

1148
01:42:37,000 --> 01:42:42,000
But it wasn't until centuries later the scientific approach was perfected in Europe,

1149
01:42:42,000 --> 01:42:49,000
mainly in 15th and 16th centuries through the works of scientists such as Copernicus, Galileo and Newton.

1150
01:42:49,000 --> 01:42:57,000
During this period, the English philosopher and scientist and politician Francis Bacon, who lived between 1561 and 1626,

1151
01:42:57,000 --> 01:43:00,000
looked at knowledge from an empirical point of view.

1152
01:43:00,000 --> 01:43:05,000
He graduated from Cambridge University and is often considered the first empiricist.

1153
01:43:05,000 --> 01:43:11,000
A school of philosophy later developed by other British philosophers such as John Locke and David Hume.

1154
01:43:11,000 --> 01:43:16,000
Bacon placed the source of knowledge in our experience through our senses.

1155
01:43:16,000 --> 01:43:21,000
At the time, the church held the view that knowledge came from God and science was challenging that.

1156
01:43:21,000 --> 01:43:25,000
Church relied on people not knowing and not questioning things.

1157
01:43:25,000 --> 01:43:30,000
When nobody knows things, the church could control information and become the source of knowledge.

1158
01:43:30,000 --> 01:43:34,000
Today you could say that big media companies have the same mindset.

1159
01:43:34,000 --> 01:43:39,000
But Francis Bacon understood the power of knowledge and wanted to educate everyone

1160
01:43:39,000 --> 01:43:44,000
because he believed that through knowledge you could empower the poor so they could live better lives.

1161
01:43:44,000 --> 01:43:48,000
This is an early idea of public education, which today we take for granted.

1162
01:43:48,000 --> 01:43:52,000
Bacon understood that humans are on the one hand knowledge seekers,

1163
01:43:52,000 --> 01:44:00,000
but on the other hand humans also have some blind spots like religious belief, tribal affiliations and love of many,

1164
01:44:00,000 --> 01:44:02,000
which prevent us from getting to the truth.

1165
01:44:02,000 --> 01:44:08,000
Another problem we have as humans is that we project our own limited experience to the world.

1166
01:44:08,000 --> 01:44:15,000
Bacon argued that science, however, doesn't look at an individual but looks at the majority to generalize.

1167
01:44:15,000 --> 01:44:19,000
It's through generalization that you get closer to the truth.

1168
01:44:19,000 --> 01:44:24,000
For instance, if one person experiences something, it's subjective and unreliable.

1169
01:44:24,000 --> 01:44:32,000
But if let's say 10, 20, 100 or more people experience the same thing, then you can generalize and make science out of it.

1170
01:44:32,000 --> 01:44:36,000
Understanding generality is an immense power according to Francis Bacon.

1171
01:44:36,000 --> 01:44:42,000
So knowledge not only opens the knower's mind, it also empowers them to change their lives for the better.

1172
01:44:42,000 --> 01:44:46,000
Of course, Bacon lived at a time when people had very little,

1173
01:44:46,000 --> 01:44:50,000
so education and knowledge could transform a person's life immeasurably.

1174
01:44:51,000 --> 01:45:02,000
Desiderius Erasmus, who lived between 1466 and 1536, was a Dutch philosopher who wrote a very influential book called In Praise of Folly.

1175
01:45:02,000 --> 01:45:09,000
Unlike Francis Bacon, Erasmus argued to be happy, naivety and ignorance are far more important than knowing.

1176
01:45:09,000 --> 01:45:13,000
For him, the purpose of life is not to gain power but to be content.

1177
01:45:13,000 --> 01:45:19,000
He was writing at a time when Europe was waking up to have a renaissance, a resurgence in scientific and rational pursuit,

1178
01:45:19,000 --> 01:45:23,000
which went against the teachings of the Church to have faith in God.

1179
01:45:23,000 --> 01:45:28,000
Erasmus, a Christian himself, while criticizing the corruption in the Catholic Church,

1180
01:45:28,000 --> 01:45:33,000
argued that to be happy, a little faith and ignorance were vitally important.

1181
01:45:33,000 --> 01:45:38,000
His philosophy was taken up by fiction writers such as Cervante, the author of Don Quixote,

1182
01:45:38,000 --> 01:45:41,000
and later the Russian writer Fyodor Dostoevsky.

1183
01:45:41,000 --> 01:45:45,000
The goal of life is not to know everything but to lead a simple life.

1184
01:45:45,000 --> 01:45:49,000
Knowledge or power doesn't make you happy but simplicity and folly do.

1185
01:45:49,000 --> 01:45:57,000
It's the old adage that ignorance is bliss which goes completely counter to the age of the Enlightenment and rationality.

1186
01:45:57,000 --> 01:46:02,000
So Erasmus said that being an idiot was the surest way to be happy.

1187
01:46:04,000 --> 01:46:11,000
Michel de Monten, who lived between 1533 and 1592, was a French philosopher who had a very curious childhood.

1188
01:46:11,000 --> 01:46:17,000
Although born into a wealthy family, he spent his first three years of childhood in the house of a peasant,

1189
01:46:17,000 --> 01:46:20,000
so he could learn the life of the poor.

1190
01:46:20,000 --> 01:46:23,000
This must have had a profound influence on him later in life.

1191
01:46:23,000 --> 01:46:27,000
If Erasmus said folly was a good medicine for happiness,

1192
01:46:27,000 --> 01:46:31,000
Monten argued that to be happy one should have a simple life.

1193
01:46:31,000 --> 01:46:36,000
Instead of seeking the company of many people, one should try to live a more solitary life

1194
01:46:36,000 --> 01:46:41,000
because society can corrupt you, either morally or intellectually.

1195
01:46:41,000 --> 01:46:46,000
In today's social media world of chasing lives and online attention and validation,

1196
01:46:46,000 --> 01:46:49,000
his message resonates with a lot of people.

1197
01:46:49,000 --> 01:46:53,000
We always try to seek the validation of our peers like some addictive drug

1198
01:46:53,000 --> 01:46:56,000
to an extent that we are never satisfied.

1199
01:46:56,000 --> 01:47:02,000
Monten says to have a peaceful life, don't chase other people's approval or glory or fame,

1200
01:47:02,000 --> 01:47:06,000
which makes us pretentious and fake most of the time.

1201
01:47:06,000 --> 01:47:09,000
He argued that attention seekers are not original thinkers,

1202
01:47:09,000 --> 01:47:13,000
but rather suffers from herd mentality or tribalism,

1203
01:47:13,000 --> 01:47:17,000
which in the heat of the crowd or moment turns us into mobs.

1204
01:47:17,000 --> 01:47:22,000
We commit horrendous crimes and only later realize how stupid it was.

1205
01:47:22,000 --> 01:47:28,000
To prevent becoming a mob, Monten argued once you disentangle yourself from the group, crowd or mobs,

1206
01:47:28,000 --> 01:47:32,000
you develop a clarity of mind or inner tranquility.

1207
01:47:32,000 --> 01:47:38,000
It's not only good for your happiness, but it's also good for your intellectual and moral integrity

1208
01:47:38,000 --> 01:47:41,000
because solitude allows you to develop yourself.

1209
01:47:41,000 --> 01:47:48,000
To have a lasting name, writers and artists should not be bogged down to social, political and tribal issues of the day.

1210
01:47:48,000 --> 01:47:52,000
Monten's idea of solitude also inspired Frederick Nietzsche,

1211
01:47:52,000 --> 01:47:57,000
who was extremely critical of the masses or mobs or tribal thinking.

1212
01:47:57,000 --> 01:47:59,000
I'll discuss Nietzsche later on.

1213
01:47:59,000 --> 01:48:05,000
As modernity made mass education the norm and the crowded cities' habitat for the majority of people,

1214
01:48:05,000 --> 01:48:09,000
life's meaning became even more acute for the modern man.

1215
01:48:09,000 --> 01:48:13,000
Knowledge of the world wasn't enough to have a meaningful life.

1216
01:48:13,000 --> 01:48:16,000
We needed something else.

1217
01:48:16,000 --> 01:48:21,000
Martin Heidegger, who lived between 1889 and 1976,

1218
01:48:21,000 --> 01:48:24,000
was a German philosopher who turned the lens onto himself.

1219
01:48:25,000 --> 01:48:29,000
Francis Bacon, like Aristotle, was interested in knowing the outside world,

1220
01:48:29,000 --> 01:48:34,000
but Heidegger, like Diagonus of Sinop, wanted to know the human being itself.

1221
01:48:34,000 --> 01:48:39,000
In his famous book, Being in Time, instead of asking what human being is,

1222
01:48:39,000 --> 01:48:42,000
he asked how it is like to be human.

1223
01:48:42,000 --> 01:48:44,000
What is that experience like?

1224
01:48:44,000 --> 01:48:45,000
Why?

1225
01:48:45,000 --> 01:48:50,000
The simple answer is that we are scientists who happen to be also the subject of science.

1226
01:48:50,000 --> 01:48:53,000
When you study animals, we are outsiders.

1227
01:48:53,000 --> 01:48:56,000
But when we study human beings, we are insiders.

1228
01:48:56,000 --> 01:48:59,000
Heidegger didn't want to have an abstract answer,

1229
01:48:59,000 --> 01:49:03,000
instead he wanted to know to have a concrete answer to the question of being,

1230
01:49:03,000 --> 01:49:07,000
which is incidentally the root of the word ontology in Greek.

1231
01:49:07,000 --> 01:49:09,000
So what is his answer?

1232
01:49:09,000 --> 01:49:12,000
Heidegger measured life as a finite phenomena,

1233
01:49:12,000 --> 01:49:15,000
starting at birth, end, ending, and death,

1234
01:49:15,000 --> 01:49:18,000
just a line that has a beginning and an end.

1235
01:49:18,000 --> 01:49:21,000
Now, unlike other animals, we know death.

1236
01:49:21,000 --> 01:49:23,000
We even anticipate it.

1237
01:49:23,000 --> 01:49:26,000
The knowledge of death makes us anxious and fearful,

1238
01:49:26,000 --> 01:49:30,000
so to cope, we tend to not think about it on a daily basis.

1239
01:49:30,000 --> 01:49:32,000
It's either a coping mechanism,

1240
01:49:32,000 --> 01:49:35,000
or simply we do not have time to think about it every day,

1241
01:49:35,000 --> 01:49:38,000
as we are busy with work and life.

1242
01:49:38,000 --> 01:49:41,000
So we are the being who is aware of death,

1243
01:49:41,000 --> 01:49:43,000
but we also try not to think about it.

1244
01:49:43,000 --> 01:49:45,000
That's precisely Heidegger's answer.

1245
01:49:45,000 --> 01:49:49,000
Human beings, or being in general, is to be aware of death.

1246
01:49:49,000 --> 01:49:52,000
Instead of making us anxious or depressed,

1247
01:49:52,000 --> 01:49:54,000
he thinks it empowers us.

1248
01:49:54,000 --> 01:49:58,000
This knowledge of death gives our life authenticity and meaning.

1249
01:49:58,000 --> 01:50:01,000
So if Bacon said knowledge of the world empowers us

1250
01:50:01,000 --> 01:50:03,000
to better our life physically,

1251
01:50:03,000 --> 01:50:05,000
Heidegger says the knowledge of death

1252
01:50:05,000 --> 01:50:10,000
gives our life meaning and empowers us to live fully and authentically.

1253
01:50:11,000 --> 01:50:15,000
Bertrand Russell, who lived between 1872 and 1970,

1254
01:50:15,000 --> 01:50:18,000
was a British philosopher who was deeply steeped

1255
01:50:18,000 --> 01:50:21,000
in the logical and mathematical side of philosophy,

1256
01:50:21,000 --> 01:50:24,000
just like Ludwig Wittgenstein, whom he influenced.

1257
01:50:24,000 --> 01:50:27,000
He used a logical and rational approach to argue

1258
01:50:27,000 --> 01:50:30,000
that to be happy one should work less.

1259
01:50:30,000 --> 01:50:32,000
You could say he is responding to Marx,

1260
01:50:32,000 --> 01:50:35,000
who argued that workers are exploited by the rich.

1261
01:50:35,000 --> 01:50:39,000
But he is also responding to the Northern European work ethics,

1262
01:50:39,000 --> 01:50:42,000
which states that work is morally good in itself.

1263
01:50:42,000 --> 01:50:45,000
Therefore, this morality, according to some,

1264
01:50:45,000 --> 01:50:48,000
was responsible for the modern capitalism.

1265
01:50:48,000 --> 01:50:51,000
Russell, however, argued that seeing work as a morally good thing

1266
01:50:51,000 --> 01:50:53,000
was not only irrational,

1267
01:50:53,000 --> 01:50:55,000
but it also made a few people very rich,

1268
01:50:55,000 --> 01:50:58,000
while the majority very unhappy.

1269
01:50:58,000 --> 01:51:01,000
Why? Because not all kinds of work are the same.

1270
01:51:01,000 --> 01:51:03,000
Some are good and some are not good.

1271
01:51:03,000 --> 01:51:05,000
Some are meaningful and some are not.

1272
01:51:05,000 --> 01:51:09,000
To bundle all as a good thing is not logical.

1273
01:51:09,000 --> 01:51:13,000
He concluded that working less increases human happiness,

1274
01:51:13,000 --> 01:51:15,000
so instead of working yourself to death,

1275
01:51:15,000 --> 01:51:17,000
you should enjoy life more.

1276
01:51:17,000 --> 01:51:18,000
Do other activities.

1277
01:51:18,000 --> 01:51:21,000
Today, a lot of people are so busy working long hours

1278
01:51:21,000 --> 01:51:24,000
that they lose sight of their well-being and happiness.

1279
01:51:24,000 --> 01:51:26,000
This is especially true for men,

1280
01:51:26,000 --> 01:51:28,000
because we are so drawn to numbers,

1281
01:51:28,000 --> 01:51:30,000
just like Bertrand Russell was.

1282
01:51:30,000 --> 01:51:33,000
We watch growth graphs and become obsessed with it.

1283
01:51:33,000 --> 01:51:36,000
We work one day and then extrapolate that to a week,

1284
01:51:36,000 --> 01:51:38,000
a month, and then a year.

1285
01:51:38,000 --> 01:51:40,000
So if we work this many days,

1286
01:51:40,000 --> 01:51:42,000
we will have this much money,

1287
01:51:42,000 --> 01:51:44,000
or as a result, we'll lose sight of the fact

1288
01:51:44,000 --> 01:51:46,000
that life is meant to be lived, not work to death.

1289
01:51:46,000 --> 01:51:49,000
So Russell argued that to be happy, work less.

1290
01:51:49,000 --> 01:51:52,000
He lived to be 90 years old.

1291
01:51:52,000 --> 01:51:56,000
Michel Foucault, who lived between 1926 and 1984,

1292
01:51:56,000 --> 01:51:58,000
was a French philosopher.

1293
01:51:58,000 --> 01:52:00,000
Unlike Bacon and Heidegger,

1294
01:52:00,000 --> 01:52:03,000
he saw knowledge as a cynical tool of repression.

1295
01:52:03,000 --> 01:52:06,000
Foucault looked at modernity through the lens of Nietzsche,

1296
01:52:06,000 --> 01:52:10,000
saying that modern rationality wasn't liberating humans,

1297
01:52:10,000 --> 01:52:13,000
but creating a more robust change of controllers.

1298
01:52:13,000 --> 01:52:16,000
He famously studied the prison system

1299
01:52:16,000 --> 01:52:18,000
and how prisons are designed to control us,

1300
01:52:18,000 --> 01:52:20,000
either directly through imprisonment

1301
01:52:20,000 --> 01:52:23,000
or indirectly through the fear of it.

1302
01:52:23,000 --> 01:52:26,000
He argued that those who have access to science and knowledge

1303
01:52:26,000 --> 01:52:29,000
use it to discipline the rest of us.

1304
01:52:29,000 --> 01:52:32,000
Foucault argued that knowledge is a tool.

1305
01:52:32,000 --> 01:52:33,000
Science is a tool.

1306
01:52:33,000 --> 01:52:35,000
Rationality is a tool.

1307
01:52:35,000 --> 01:52:37,000
But mostly for the powerful elite

1308
01:52:37,000 --> 01:52:39,000
because they have access to all of them,

1309
01:52:39,000 --> 01:52:42,000
while the majority of us start subjects.

1310
01:52:42,000 --> 01:52:45,000
Michel Foucault was also inspired by Emmanuel Kahn,

1311
01:52:45,000 --> 01:52:47,000
whose epistemological revolution argued

1312
01:52:47,000 --> 01:52:50,000
that our knowledge of reality is not totally objective.

1313
01:52:50,000 --> 01:52:53,000
But rather, we see the world the way we see

1314
01:52:53,000 --> 01:52:56,000
because we impose our own mental structure on the world.

1315
01:52:56,000 --> 01:52:59,000
Foucault even argued that man or mankind itself

1316
01:52:59,000 --> 01:53:02,000
is a recent invention.

1317
01:53:02,000 --> 01:53:04,000
So to sum up, on the knowledge side,

1318
01:53:04,000 --> 01:53:07,000
Francis Bacon understood that our knowledge of the world

1319
01:53:07,000 --> 01:53:09,000
could empower us to better our lives.

1320
01:53:09,000 --> 01:53:11,000
Heidegger argued that our knowledge of death

1321
01:53:11,000 --> 01:53:14,000
can give our life more meaning and authenticity.

1322
01:53:14,000 --> 01:53:17,000
Foucault, however, said everything is invented.

1323
01:53:17,000 --> 01:53:19,000
There is nothing solid to understand.

1324
01:53:19,000 --> 01:53:21,000
Knowledge is just a tool for power

1325
01:53:21,000 --> 01:53:24,000
to manipulate nature and other humans.

1326
01:53:24,000 --> 01:53:26,000
So to sum up on the happiness side,

1327
01:53:26,000 --> 01:53:29,000
Erasmus argued that folly, ignorance, or naivety

1328
01:53:29,000 --> 01:53:32,000
is a good thing to have to lead a happier life.

1329
01:53:32,000 --> 01:53:34,000
We have all seen children.

1330
01:53:34,000 --> 01:53:36,000
When we grow older, we lose that naivety

1331
01:53:36,000 --> 01:53:38,000
and become a bit more miserable.

1332
01:53:38,000 --> 01:53:40,000
Monten argued that don't follow the crowd

1333
01:53:40,000 --> 01:53:44,000
and seek some solitude to cultivate your own inner peace.

1334
01:53:44,000 --> 01:53:48,000
Don't seek validation from others like a drug addict.

1335
01:53:48,000 --> 01:53:52,000
The higher you go, the more you seek to get high and higher.

1336
01:53:52,000 --> 01:53:54,000
New mountain is high enough.

1337
01:53:54,000 --> 01:53:57,000
So listen to Monten because he came down the mountain

1338
01:53:57,000 --> 01:53:59,000
to settle in a hut.

1339
01:53:59,000 --> 01:54:02,000
Even his name is Monten, so climb yourself and your ego,

1340
01:54:02,000 --> 01:54:04,000
not other people's validations.

1341
01:54:04,000 --> 01:54:07,000
Bertrand Russell argued that work is not morally good

1342
01:54:07,000 --> 01:54:11,000
or bad thing, so we should prioritize happiness over work.

1343
01:54:11,000 --> 01:54:13,000
Work to live or live to work.

1344
01:54:13,000 --> 01:54:15,000
I should really listen to this,

1345
01:54:15,000 --> 01:54:17,000
but I want to have more subscribers.

1346
01:54:17,000 --> 01:54:19,000
Monten, help.

1347
01:54:20,000 --> 01:54:23,000
So knowledge can make your physical life better

1348
01:54:23,000 --> 01:54:25,000
or make you more successful financially

1349
01:54:25,000 --> 01:54:27,000
or boost your social standing,

1350
01:54:27,000 --> 01:54:30,000
but it might decrease your overall happiness.

1351
01:54:30,000 --> 01:54:32,000
Knowing things also makes us human

1352
01:54:32,000 --> 01:54:34,000
very cynical about the world,

1353
01:54:34,000 --> 01:54:36,000
just like Foucault said that all knowledge is power

1354
01:54:36,000 --> 01:54:38,000
and all authorities won't suppress you.

1355
01:54:38,000 --> 01:54:40,000
Naivety, on the other hand,

1356
01:54:40,000 --> 01:54:42,000
might make your physical life harder

1357
01:54:42,000 --> 01:54:44,000
as you don't have everything figured out,

1358
01:54:44,000 --> 01:54:47,000
but it can also lead you to a more long-lasting happiness

1359
01:54:47,000 --> 01:54:50,000
as you trust other people and rely on other people,

1360
01:54:50,000 --> 01:54:52,000
which brings the level of sincerity in yourself

1361
01:54:52,000 --> 01:54:54,000
and those around you.

1362
01:54:54,000 --> 01:54:56,000
So knowledge makes you successful,

1363
01:54:56,000 --> 01:54:58,000
but it could also make you cynical.

1364
01:54:58,000 --> 01:55:00,000
While ignorance hinders your success,

1365
01:55:00,000 --> 01:55:02,000
it could also lead to a more blissful life.

1366
01:55:02,000 --> 01:55:04,000
What do you think?

1367
01:55:04,000 --> 01:55:06,000
Next, I'll discuss a battle between rationalists

1368
01:55:06,000 --> 01:55:09,000
and empiricists, leading to Immanuel Kant's

1369
01:55:09,000 --> 01:55:12,000
great breakthrough in philosophical knowledge.

1370
01:55:13,000 --> 01:55:16,000
Previously, I discussed the question

1371
01:55:16,000 --> 01:55:18,000
whether our life purpose is to seek knowledge

1372
01:55:18,000 --> 01:55:20,000
or seek happiness.

1373
01:55:20,000 --> 01:55:22,000
In this segment, I'll look at one of the biggest battles

1374
01:55:22,000 --> 01:55:24,000
in philosophy between the rationalists,

1375
01:55:24,000 --> 01:55:26,000
mostly mainland Europeans,

1376
01:55:26,000 --> 01:55:29,000
who argue that knowledge is somewhat innate inside us,

1377
01:55:29,000 --> 01:55:31,000
and empiricists, mainly British,

1378
01:55:31,000 --> 01:55:34,000
who argue that knowledge comes from experience.

1379
01:55:34,000 --> 01:55:36,000
Immanuel Kant brought the two together.

1380
01:55:36,000 --> 01:55:38,000
If Western philosophy was a two-sided funnel,

1381
01:55:38,000 --> 01:55:40,000
Kant would be the narrow part,

1382
01:55:40,000 --> 01:55:43,000
so everything before him is squeezed through him

1383
01:55:43,000 --> 01:55:45,000
and after him, Hegel and Schopenhauer

1384
01:55:45,000 --> 01:55:48,000
move philosophy in two different directions.

1385
01:55:48,000 --> 01:55:50,000
Hegel went historical and rational,

1386
01:55:50,000 --> 01:55:53,000
while Schopenhauer went psychological and subconscious.

1387
01:55:53,000 --> 01:55:57,000
I'll discuss these two philosophical approaches later on.

1388
01:55:57,000 --> 01:55:59,000
Rationalism is a school of philosophy

1389
01:55:59,000 --> 01:56:02,000
that relies on human reason to understand the world.

1390
01:56:02,000 --> 01:56:05,000
Reason itself is an innate human property.

1391
01:56:05,000 --> 01:56:08,000
In other words, we're born with the ability to reason,

1392
01:56:08,000 --> 01:56:12,000
early rationalists saw reason as God-given gift.

1393
01:56:12,000 --> 01:56:14,000
The father of rationalism is René Descartes,

1394
01:56:14,000 --> 01:56:17,000
who lived between 1596 and 1650.

1395
01:56:17,000 --> 01:56:19,000
He was a French philosopher and a scientist

1396
01:56:19,000 --> 01:56:22,000
who famously did his thought experiment.

1397
01:56:22,000 --> 01:56:25,000
He sat down in his armchair and asked the simple question,

1398
01:56:25,000 --> 01:56:27,000
what if everything we know is just a dream?

1399
01:56:27,000 --> 01:56:29,000
Nothing exists in reality.

1400
01:56:29,000 --> 01:56:31,000
In other words, to prove that he existed,

1401
01:56:31,000 --> 01:56:33,000
he did the opposite.

1402
01:56:33,000 --> 01:56:35,000
He doubted his own existence.

1403
01:56:35,000 --> 01:56:37,000
Then he said, if everything was a dream,

1404
01:56:37,000 --> 01:56:39,000
the dreamer has to be real,

1405
01:56:39,000 --> 01:56:42,000
otherwise there will be no dreaming without a dreamer

1406
01:56:42,000 --> 01:56:44,000
or doubt without a doubter.

1407
01:56:44,000 --> 01:56:47,000
So he said the most famous line in philosophy,

1408
01:56:47,000 --> 01:56:49,000
I think therefore I am.

1409
01:56:49,000 --> 01:56:52,000
Even if you doubt your own existence, this doubt is real.

1410
01:56:52,000 --> 01:56:55,000
According to Descartes, we get knowledge or ideas

1411
01:56:55,000 --> 01:56:57,000
in three different ways.

1412
01:56:57,000 --> 01:57:00,000
Some come from our experience, some drive from reason,

1413
01:57:00,000 --> 01:57:03,000
and some ideas are innate inside us,

1414
01:57:03,000 --> 01:57:05,000
presumably from God.

1415
01:57:05,000 --> 01:57:07,000
Scientists like René Descartes argue

1416
01:57:07,000 --> 01:57:09,000
that we have an innate knowledge of the world

1417
01:57:09,000 --> 01:57:12,000
and as we grow, we simply unfold that knowledge

1418
01:57:12,000 --> 01:57:14,000
to see things more clearly.

1419
01:57:14,000 --> 01:57:16,000
In a way, rationalists are like Plato

1420
01:57:16,000 --> 01:57:19,000
and saying that our knowledge of the world inside us

1421
01:57:19,000 --> 01:57:22,000
and learning is just recollection of that innate knowledge.

1422
01:57:22,000 --> 01:57:25,000
So the seed is inside us, not outside.

1423
01:57:25,000 --> 01:57:28,000
The other famous rationalist was Gottfried Leibniz,

1424
01:57:28,000 --> 01:57:31,000
who lived between 1646 and 1716.

1425
01:57:31,000 --> 01:57:34,000
Today we know him more because of the famous argument

1426
01:57:34,000 --> 01:57:38,000
he had with Isaac Newton over the invention of calculus.

1427
01:57:38,000 --> 01:57:40,000
Leibniz, however, was a great philosopher

1428
01:57:40,000 --> 01:57:43,000
who made a distinction between rational truth and factual truth.

1429
01:57:43,000 --> 01:57:45,000
In other words, our knowledge of the world

1430
01:57:45,000 --> 01:57:49,000
relies on our innate reason, but also on human experience.

1431
01:57:49,000 --> 01:57:51,000
The things we experience on the outside

1432
01:57:51,000 --> 01:57:55,000
builds on and solidifies our inner knowledge.

1433
01:57:55,000 --> 01:57:58,000
For Leibniz, the human mind is a small representation

1434
01:57:58,000 --> 01:58:00,000
of the entire universe.

1435
01:58:00,000 --> 01:58:02,000
In other words, the human mind contains everything

1436
01:58:02,000 --> 01:58:04,000
in the universe.

1437
01:58:04,000 --> 01:58:06,000
If the universe is rational, then the human mind

1438
01:58:06,000 --> 01:58:08,000
is a representation of that rationality.

1439
01:58:08,000 --> 01:58:11,000
However, he conceded that human rationality

1440
01:58:11,000 --> 01:58:14,000
is not always adequate to understand the world,

1441
01:58:14,000 --> 01:58:18,000
so we need human experience to complement our rational faculties.

1442
01:58:18,000 --> 01:58:21,000
One of the biggest problems for Leibniz was his belief in God,

1443
01:58:21,000 --> 01:58:25,000
so he attempted to reconcile scientific empiricism

1444
01:58:25,000 --> 01:58:27,000
with the idea of God, who knows it all.

1445
01:58:27,000 --> 01:58:31,000
In doing so, Leibniz argued for two different forms of truth.

1446
01:58:31,000 --> 01:58:34,000
The empirical truths we get through experiences

1447
01:58:34,000 --> 01:58:38,000
add to our rational truth, which we innately have or God given.

1448
01:58:38,000 --> 01:58:41,000
So to sum up, rationalists argue that humans are

1449
01:58:41,000 --> 01:58:44,000
naturally equipped to utilize reason to understand the world

1450
01:58:44,000 --> 01:58:48,000
with or without the need of observation or animal senses.

1451
01:58:48,000 --> 01:58:51,000
In other words, we don't need experiences to know the world.

1452
01:58:51,000 --> 01:58:53,000
We simply know it because, for the most part,

1453
01:58:53,000 --> 01:58:56,000
God has imparted us with innate knowledge

1454
01:58:56,000 --> 01:58:58,000
or ability of reasoning.

1455
01:58:58,000 --> 01:59:01,000
Empiricism, however, disagreed, saying that we understand the world

1456
01:59:01,000 --> 01:59:04,000
not innately, but through experience in empirical data

1457
01:59:04,000 --> 01:59:07,000
we gather from the world through our human senses.

1458
01:59:07,000 --> 01:59:11,000
Our mind is a blank slate without experience.

1459
01:59:12,000 --> 01:59:16,000
John Locke, who lived between 1632 and 1704, argued

1460
01:59:16,000 --> 01:59:20,000
around the same time as Leibniz was a pioneer of empiricism

1461
01:59:20,000 --> 01:59:22,000
who said that everything we know about the world

1462
01:59:22,000 --> 01:59:24,000
has come to us from our experience.

1463
01:59:24,000 --> 01:59:27,000
He gave the example of newborn babies to show

1464
01:59:27,000 --> 01:59:30,000
that we humans have not a single idea from birth.

1465
01:59:30,000 --> 01:59:34,000
We simply learn by observing and experiencing things.

1466
01:59:34,000 --> 01:59:37,000
Quote, if we attentively consider newborn children

1467
01:59:37,000 --> 01:59:39,000
we shall have little reason to think

1468
01:59:39,000 --> 01:59:42,000
that they bring many ideas into the world with them.

1469
01:59:42,000 --> 01:59:46,000
Locke understood that while we may not have innate ideas from birth

1470
01:59:46,000 --> 01:59:50,000
we do have the ability to learn a language, which may be innate.

1471
01:59:50,000 --> 01:59:52,000
This was later developed by Noam Chomsky

1472
01:59:52,000 --> 01:59:55,000
in his famous theory of universal grammar

1473
01:59:55,000 --> 01:59:58,000
that humans were a hardware to learn a language in its structure.

1474
01:59:58,000 --> 02:00:01,000
So John Locke concluded that all knowledge we gain

1475
02:00:01,000 --> 02:00:04,000
we gain through experience.

1476
02:00:06,000 --> 02:00:10,000
David Hume, who lived between 1711 and 1776

1477
02:00:10,000 --> 02:00:13,000
built on John Locke's idea of empirical experience

1478
02:00:13,000 --> 02:00:16,000
as a source of knowledge and further argued

1479
02:00:16,000 --> 02:00:19,000
that not only we understand the world through observation experiences

1480
02:00:19,000 --> 02:00:23,000
but we're also able to categorize things as a kind of customer habit

1481
02:00:23,000 --> 02:00:25,000
which guides us through life.

1482
02:00:25,000 --> 02:00:29,000
Hume argues that if you see a tree then another, then another

1483
02:00:29,000 --> 02:00:32,000
at some point you see a pattern or category.

1484
02:00:32,000 --> 02:00:34,000
This you call trees.

1485
02:00:34,000 --> 02:00:36,000
We have no notion of trees from birth.

1486
02:00:36,000 --> 02:00:38,000
We are like blank slits as babies

1487
02:00:38,000 --> 02:00:41,000
and only through encounters with the outside world

1488
02:00:41,000 --> 02:00:44,000
we begin to form knowledge of the outside world.

1489
02:00:44,000 --> 02:00:46,000
The same with night and day.

1490
02:00:46,000 --> 02:00:48,000
As you see the cycle being repeated

1491
02:00:48,000 --> 02:00:51,000
you begin to expect it as a kind of custom that night turns into day

1492
02:00:51,000 --> 02:00:53,000
and day turns into night

1493
02:00:53,000 --> 02:00:55,000
and the cycle becomes a customary knowledge.

1494
02:00:55,000 --> 02:00:58,000
This over time becomes ideas and beliefs.

1495
02:00:58,000 --> 02:01:02,000
Over time they turn into what is called innate knowledge.

1496
02:01:02,000 --> 02:01:06,000
Hume says there are nothing but old impressions or perceptions over time.

1497
02:01:06,000 --> 02:01:09,000
As knowledge is passed on from generation to generation

1498
02:01:09,000 --> 02:01:13,000
it may seem innate which is nothing but someone's experience.

1499
02:01:13,000 --> 02:01:17,000
So David Hume added custom as a kind of repeated experience

1500
02:01:17,000 --> 02:01:19,000
or common knowledge

1501
02:01:19,000 --> 02:01:23,000
and argued that we learn things from experience it is not innate.

1502
02:01:23,000 --> 02:01:28,000
So the rationalists believe we humans are equipped with some innate knowledge of the world at birth

1503
02:01:28,000 --> 02:01:31,000
while the empiricists argue that we are blank slits

1504
02:01:31,000 --> 02:01:34,000
and only through our experiences we gain knowledge of the world.

1505
02:01:34,000 --> 02:01:38,000
In other words, rationalists see knowledge flow from inside out

1506
02:01:38,000 --> 02:01:41,000
like a torch shedding light on the outside

1507
02:01:41,000 --> 02:01:46,000
while the empiricists see knowledge flow from outside like a window lighting a room.

1508
02:01:47,000 --> 02:01:53,000
Here comes the German giant Immanuel Kant who lived between 1724 and 1804.

1509
02:01:53,000 --> 02:01:58,000
Kant took up the challenge of reconciling these two divergent schools of philosophy.

1510
02:01:58,000 --> 02:02:01,000
To solve the problem between the rationalists and the empiricists

1511
02:02:01,000 --> 02:02:05,000
Kant devised a new theory that divided the world into two

1512
02:02:05,000 --> 02:02:07,000
phenomena and numina.

1513
02:02:07,000 --> 02:02:09,000
Phenomena is a world of experiences

1514
02:02:09,000 --> 02:02:12,000
how we understand the world through our bodily senses.

1515
02:02:12,000 --> 02:02:16,000
Things we see, hear, touch and smell in observing study.

1516
02:02:16,000 --> 02:02:20,000
Numina on the other hand is a world in itself which we can never truly know.

1517
02:02:20,000 --> 02:02:23,000
For example, we can touch and study a rock

1518
02:02:23,000 --> 02:02:26,000
but we cannot truly understand what it feels to be a rock.

1519
02:02:26,000 --> 02:02:29,000
As a result, our knowledge of the rock is not complete.

1520
02:02:29,000 --> 02:02:31,000
It's limited and partial.

1521
02:02:31,000 --> 02:02:34,000
Kant argued that when we are receiving information through experience

1522
02:02:34,000 --> 02:02:36,000
however we are not passive receivers

1523
02:02:36,000 --> 02:02:40,000
instead we humans also impose our own structures to the world.

1524
02:02:40,000 --> 02:02:44,000
We categorize things into rocks, trees, animals and what not.

1525
02:02:44,000 --> 02:02:49,000
The world we see is a reflection of a mental structure we put out to the world.

1526
02:02:49,000 --> 02:02:52,000
Rocks and trees may not have any notion of being such

1527
02:02:52,000 --> 02:02:56,000
but humans have imposed such categories onto them.

1528
02:02:56,000 --> 02:02:59,000
In other words, we are not passive knowledge receivers

1529
02:02:59,000 --> 02:03:03,000
but actively imposing our own structure on things.

1530
02:03:03,000 --> 02:03:06,000
Now Kant brings the rationalists and empiricists together.

1531
02:03:06,000 --> 02:03:11,000
Rationalists argue everything is inside us while empiricists say everything is outside us

1532
02:03:11,000 --> 02:03:16,000
and Kant says we are sort of on the threshold of outside and inside

1533
02:03:16,000 --> 02:03:20,000
like a kind of window glass in the middle of inside and outside.

1534
02:03:20,000 --> 02:03:25,000
Our inner mental structure shapes how we experience the world.

1535
02:03:25,000 --> 02:03:27,000
For example, a good analogy would be fishing.

1536
02:03:27,000 --> 02:03:30,000
To catch a fish, a fisherman throws a net.

1537
02:03:30,000 --> 02:03:34,000
If the holes in the net are too large, the fish escape

1538
02:03:34,000 --> 02:03:38,000
and if the net has no hole, it catches more water than fish.

1539
02:03:38,000 --> 02:03:43,000
So the fish is the outside world why the net we throw is our mental structure

1540
02:03:43,000 --> 02:03:46,000
we put out to capture the experience as knowledge.

1541
02:03:46,000 --> 02:03:50,000
We humans probe the world through our innate mental structure

1542
02:03:50,000 --> 02:03:53,000
which catches the outside experience based knowledge.

1543
02:03:53,000 --> 02:03:57,000
So for Kant reason and experience go hand in hand in understanding the world.

1544
02:03:57,000 --> 02:03:59,000
Without the net you cannot catch.

1545
02:03:59,000 --> 02:04:03,000
You need both reason and experience to understand the world.

1546
02:04:03,000 --> 02:04:06,000
This he called his Copernican Revolution.

1547
02:04:06,000 --> 02:04:11,000
Why? Because in the Middle Ages people believed the sun was orbiting the earth

1548
02:04:11,000 --> 02:04:14,000
and Copernicus said the earth is orbiting the sun.

1549
02:04:14,000 --> 02:04:16,000
Kant did the same.

1550
02:04:16,000 --> 02:04:19,000
Empiricists say knowledge comes from outside and Kant says yes

1551
02:04:19,000 --> 02:04:22,000
but not only we actively seek the outside knowledge

1552
02:04:22,000 --> 02:04:28,000
but it also goes through us so our mental structure determines reality on the outside.

1553
02:04:28,000 --> 02:04:34,000
In other words our human method puts a structure to the world that would not exist without humans.

1554
02:04:34,000 --> 02:04:39,000
And this structure makes it easy for us to understand and manipulate the world.

1555
02:04:39,000 --> 02:04:44,000
Imagine we're not human we might have a very different understanding of the world.

1556
02:04:44,000 --> 02:04:48,000
So to sum up the rationalist thing reason is more important than experience

1557
02:04:48,000 --> 02:04:50,000
in our pursuit of knowledge.

1558
02:04:50,000 --> 02:04:54,000
Our reason is like a torch that allows us to see things.

1559
02:04:54,000 --> 02:04:59,000
The empiricists however counter argue that experience is primary and reason is secondary.

1560
02:04:59,000 --> 02:05:05,000
Our senses act like a window that lets light in so we understand things.

1561
02:05:05,000 --> 02:05:08,000
Kant says we human are both a torch and a window

1562
02:05:08,000 --> 02:05:14,000
because our mental structure allows us to experience and understand the world better faster and more effectively.

1563
02:05:14,000 --> 02:05:20,000
Without a good method or an effective tool and structure our experiences are all over the place.

1564
02:05:20,000 --> 02:05:22,000
The debate is still not over though.

1565
02:05:22,000 --> 02:05:26,000
Despite Kant uniting the two epistemological approaches in philosophy

1566
02:05:26,000 --> 02:05:29,000
there are still people who think one way or another.

1567
02:05:29,000 --> 02:05:32,000
Our modern science is leaning more to the empiricist camp

1568
02:05:32,000 --> 02:05:35,000
while most psychologists lean more towards

1569
02:05:35,000 --> 02:05:38,000
not the rationalist but the irrational subconscious

1570
02:05:38,000 --> 02:05:42,000
or the unconscious in determining how we understand the world.

1571
02:05:42,000 --> 02:05:47,000
So the debate has shifted from reason to passion in some cases to intuition.

1572
02:05:47,000 --> 02:05:51,000
It is not rationality but intuition that allows us to understand the world.

1573
02:05:51,000 --> 02:05:57,000
Next I'll discuss what motivates human action by looking at two of Kant's famous successors

1574
02:05:57,000 --> 02:05:59,000
who went in different directions.

1575
02:05:59,000 --> 02:06:03,000
Schopenhauer went psychologically towards eastern philosophy

1576
02:06:03,000 --> 02:06:06,000
while Hegel built his philosophy on history.

1577
02:06:06,000 --> 02:06:10,000
On the one hand we have Hegel, Marx, Sartre and others

1578
02:06:10,000 --> 02:06:13,000
who explain human motivation through history and rationality

1579
02:06:13,000 --> 02:06:16,000
while on the other hand Schopenhauer, Kierkegaard and Nietzsche

1580
02:06:16,000 --> 02:06:21,000
relied on individual psyche and human passion to explain human motivation.

1581
02:06:24,000 --> 02:06:29,000
Previously I discussed how Immanuel Kant bridged the two philosophical approaches

1582
02:06:29,000 --> 02:06:32,000
to epistemology, rationalism and empiricism.

1583
02:06:32,000 --> 02:06:34,000
So in western philosophy Kant is like a funnel.

1584
02:06:34,000 --> 02:06:38,000
He influenced another two branches of philosophy that came after him

1585
02:06:38,000 --> 02:06:41,000
which tried to answer some fundamental questions like

1586
02:06:41,000 --> 02:06:45,000
what makes us who we are, what motivates our actions.

1587
02:06:45,000 --> 02:06:51,000
Hegel's answer was history and rationality while his arch-rival Schopenhauer's answer was the subconscious will.

1588
02:06:51,000 --> 02:06:56,000
Hegel's philosophy went the sociological route basing human action on history and rationality

1589
02:06:56,000 --> 02:07:01,000
while Schopenhauer's philosophy went the psychological route basing human motivation

1590
02:07:01,000 --> 02:07:04,000
on the subconscious blind will or human passion.

1591
02:07:04,000 --> 02:07:09,000
In this segment I'll look at sociology and rationality by discussing philosophers

1592
02:07:09,000 --> 02:07:12,000
including Hegel, Marx, Sartre and Zezek

1593
02:07:12,000 --> 02:07:16,000
who argued that we are the product of history but they didn't stop there.

1594
02:07:16,000 --> 02:07:21,000
Since history makes us who we are it's also our job to make history

1595
02:07:21,000 --> 02:07:25,000
so we're not only molded and shaped by the historical era in which we live in

1596
02:07:25,000 --> 02:07:28,000
but also through our own life choices.

1597
02:07:28,000 --> 02:07:32,000
So social philosophy is built on the philosophy of progressive egalitarianism

1598
02:07:32,000 --> 02:07:36,000
stating that we are heading towards perfectionist utopia on the one hand

1599
02:07:36,000 --> 02:07:43,000
and materialism stating that the most important aspect of human life is material success on the other.

1600
02:07:43,000 --> 02:07:45,000
Of course not all of them agreed on this.

1601
02:07:45,000 --> 02:07:50,000
It's important to know that philosophers who came after Kant were in a sense responding to Kant

1602
02:07:50,000 --> 02:07:54,000
because his breakthrough in bringing the rationalists and imperialists together

1603
02:07:54,000 --> 02:07:57,000
was a huge moment in philosophy.

1604
02:07:58,000 --> 02:08:04,000
George Hegel who lived between 1770 and 1831 too responded to Kant.

1605
02:08:04,000 --> 02:08:06,000
Hegel had two problems with Kant.

1606
02:08:06,000 --> 02:08:10,000
First Kant argued that we humans only understand the phenomena

1607
02:08:10,000 --> 02:08:14,000
but we have no access to Númena or the thing itself.

1608
02:08:14,000 --> 02:08:17,000
We can touch a rock but we cannot fully understand it.

1609
02:08:17,000 --> 02:08:23,000
For Hegel this Númena world which we can never fully know looked like an empty abstraction

1610
02:08:23,000 --> 02:08:26,000
pure speculation based on Kant's own assumption.

1611
02:08:26,000 --> 02:08:31,000
In other words he just made it up by claiming that such a thing existed in the first place.

1612
02:08:31,000 --> 02:08:35,000
Hegel's second problem with Kant was that he argued that our innate structure

1613
02:08:35,000 --> 02:08:39,000
or categorization by which we interpret the world is fixed.

1614
02:08:39,000 --> 02:08:44,000
In other words we use a fishnet or framework by which we catch a fish or experience

1615
02:08:44,000 --> 02:08:48,000
but the net or the framework is always fixed and nobody can change it.

1616
02:08:48,000 --> 02:08:55,000
For the history buff Hegel everything including human consciousness was subject to change through time.

1617
02:08:55,000 --> 02:09:00,000
History has shown us that humans evolve so do our tools including the fishnet

1618
02:09:00,000 --> 02:09:02,000
or our ability to reason.

1619
02:09:02,000 --> 02:09:07,000
In other words everything has a history even rock has a history it changes through time

1620
02:09:07,000 --> 02:09:11,000
and humans are very much a product of historical era.

1621
02:09:11,000 --> 02:09:15,000
How do we change? Hegel says through dialectic processes.

1622
02:09:15,000 --> 02:09:21,000
When two opposites collide it makes a third thing that has a bit of both the original things

1623
02:09:21,000 --> 02:09:24,000
but it also has slightly different characters.

1624
02:09:24,000 --> 02:09:30,000
Hegel says every phenomena or idea or thesis as he called it contains a contradiction within itself

1625
02:09:30,000 --> 02:09:32,000
which he called antithesis.

1626
02:09:32,000 --> 02:09:38,000
In this conflict which is resolved in synthesis or a new idea which is an improvement

1627
02:09:38,000 --> 02:09:41,000
or different from the thesis in antithesis.

1628
02:09:41,000 --> 02:09:45,000
Like a child has a characteristic of both parents but also different from both.

1629
02:09:45,000 --> 02:09:49,000
This historical process continues in generating new thesis in antithesis

1630
02:09:49,000 --> 02:09:52,000
which lead to further synthesis and history continues.

1631
02:09:52,000 --> 02:09:57,000
So according to Hegel Kant was wrong in saying that human mental structure or reason does not change.

1632
02:09:57,000 --> 02:10:00,000
For Hegel everything is subject to change.

1633
02:10:00,000 --> 02:10:04,000
It's important to know that Kant was a lot firmer in his religious belief than Hegel

1634
02:10:04,000 --> 02:10:10,000
which explains that Kant sees reason as a static while Hegel sees it as malleable and changeable through time.

1635
02:10:10,000 --> 02:10:14,000
And that the reason was of course the French Revolution as well as the rise of Napoleon

1636
02:10:14,000 --> 02:10:19,000
which for the very first time in human history ordinary people took power from the king

1637
02:10:19,000 --> 02:10:22,000
and anyone could become Napoleon.

1638
02:10:22,000 --> 02:10:23,000
So nothing was fixed.

1639
02:10:23,000 --> 02:10:30,000
Kant being a much older man was fiercely against any kind of revolution that could destabilize the status quo.

1640
02:10:30,000 --> 02:10:35,000
For Hegel the world has a history and we are for the most part the product of historical era.

1641
02:10:35,000 --> 02:10:39,000
In other words reality is a historical process not constant.

1642
02:10:39,000 --> 02:10:43,000
However since we are the product of history we can also affect the course of history

1643
02:10:43,000 --> 02:10:46,000
through ideas that capture the spirit of an age.

1644
02:10:46,000 --> 02:10:52,000
For example Napoleon managed to influence history as he captured the spirit of 19th century Europe.

1645
02:10:52,000 --> 02:10:56,000
People didn't believe in the absolute power of kings or demanded change.

1646
02:10:56,000 --> 02:11:02,000
Hegel can be characterized as a perfectionist rationalist believing that history is moving towards perfection.

1647
02:11:02,000 --> 02:11:08,000
Now Hegel only interpreted history. His student wanted to change history.

1648
02:11:08,000 --> 02:11:15,000
Karl Marx who lived between 1818 and 1883 learned a great deal from Hegel.

1649
02:11:15,000 --> 02:11:22,000
He came to the conclusion that if we are the product of history our history must be the product of those who came before us.

1650
02:11:22,000 --> 02:11:29,000
Marx had a problem. Hegel was good at interpreting history even at recognizing the people who were capable of changing

1651
02:11:29,000 --> 02:11:33,000
but Marx was more concerned about changing things for the good

1652
02:11:33,000 --> 02:11:38,000
especially for the disadvantaged majority who were the real force behind economic production.

1653
02:11:38,000 --> 02:11:40,000
i.e. the working class.

1654
02:11:40,000 --> 02:11:47,000
Marx said the history of our existence has been nothing but a continuous class struggle between the haves and have nots

1655
02:11:47,000 --> 02:11:53,000
the powerful and the powerless with the powerful enjoying it all and the powerless having a tough time of it.

1656
02:11:53,000 --> 02:12:01,000
So Marx developed a philosophy of rational materialism arguing that material inequality was the truth of all evils.

1657
02:12:01,000 --> 02:12:08,000
He argued that humans are fundamentally motivated by material objects so we are rational because we want material things.

1658
02:12:08,000 --> 02:12:12,000
To solve this inequality he adopted egalitarianism.

1659
02:12:12,000 --> 02:12:20,000
For Marx the perfectionist future utopia was an egalitarian society where you only worked for the hours that provided you enough subsistence

1660
02:12:20,000 --> 02:12:23,000
and the rest of time you could relax on the beach.

1661
02:12:23,000 --> 02:12:30,000
You can also see traces of Christianity and Marxism the fight between good and evil culminating in the weak overthrowing the powerful

1662
02:12:30,000 --> 02:12:37,000
and turning the world into a utopian communist heaven where everyone lives equally and happily ever after.

1663
02:12:37,000 --> 02:12:45,000
But Marx was not religious so he based his philosophy on rational materialism in which all workers unite over through the exploitative class

1664
02:12:45,000 --> 02:12:49,000
and everyone lives in harmony and peace and nobody starves.

1665
02:12:49,000 --> 02:12:58,000
For Marx not only communism was desirable it was also historically inevitable because for him history was moving towards perfection

1666
02:12:58,000 --> 02:13:03,000
through incremental improvement or dialectical change as Hegel said.

1667
02:13:03,000 --> 02:13:10,000
For example feudalism was an improvement on hunter gatherer societies capitalism was an improvement on feudalism

1668
02:13:10,000 --> 02:13:15,000
socialism and improvement on capitalism and finally communism and improvement on socialism

1669
02:13:15,000 --> 02:13:19,000
and for Marx communism was the final phase of human history.

1670
02:13:19,000 --> 02:13:25,000
You couldn't make it any better just like heaven you cannot create a heaven that is better than another heaven

1671
02:13:25,000 --> 02:13:31,000
or maybe you could but generally heavens tend to mean perfection if they do exist of course.

1672
02:13:31,000 --> 02:13:40,000
Marxist class based analysis had deep communitarian roots or group based as a result it failed in a highly individualized Europe

1673
02:13:40,000 --> 02:13:46,000
despite many attempts for example in 1870s Paris had a socialist revolution but it didn't stick.

1674
02:13:46,000 --> 02:13:52,000
Marxism found fertile soil in countries with strong communitarian bond like Russia and China

1675
02:13:52,000 --> 02:13:57,000
so the 20th century witnessed many Marxist revolutions to move history in the right direction.

1676
02:13:57,000 --> 02:14:02,000
These attempts had partial success but ultimately failed to create a communist utopia.

1677
02:14:02,000 --> 02:14:08,000
So Hegel talked about history in motion Marx talked about how to speed up that historical motion

1678
02:14:08,000 --> 02:14:12,000
both Hegel and Marx saw things from a society's perspective.

1679
02:14:12,000 --> 02:14:19,000
Now I'll discuss how this history based philosophy applies to a person's own individual history from birth to death.

1680
02:14:19,000 --> 02:14:23,000
If a society has a history so does an individual.

1681
02:14:24,000 --> 02:14:30,000
Jean-Paul Sartre who lived between 1905 and 1980 was a French existentialist philosopher.

1682
02:14:30,000 --> 02:14:36,000
He was not a Marxist but was hugely influenced by Marx and other Marxists especially the Maoist movement in France.

1683
02:14:36,000 --> 02:14:43,000
Hegel and Marx both agreed that humans are not only the product of history we humans also serve the purpose of history.

1684
02:14:43,000 --> 02:14:51,000
Hegel explained reality through a godlike spirit or idea and Marx explained through a historical materialism in class struggle

1685
02:14:51,000 --> 02:14:57,000
in other words both argued that we individuals are there to serve the grander mission or purpose

1686
02:14:57,000 --> 02:15:01,000
be it God or history or class struggle or general society.

1687
02:15:01,000 --> 02:15:04,000
But what's the purpose of an individual human life?

1688
02:15:04,000 --> 02:15:08,000
Sartre's existentialist philosophy argued that human life has no purpose

1689
02:15:08,000 --> 02:15:14,000
because we are made neither by God nor by a blind force of history as Marx and Hegel outlined.

1690
02:15:14,000 --> 02:15:18,000
Instead we are made by our own history choices we make in our own life

1691
02:15:18,000 --> 02:15:21,000
in other words we have no essence or purpose from birth

1692
02:15:21,000 --> 02:15:26,000
we simply acquire it through our life often through our own free choices in actions.

1693
02:15:26,000 --> 02:15:32,000
Since we have no pre-ordained purpose set for us by some other power like God or society

1694
02:15:32,000 --> 02:15:36,000
we are free to make mistakes to find our own purpose.

1695
02:15:36,000 --> 02:15:41,000
Sartre even goes further by saying that we are condemned to be free and condemned to make mistakes

1696
02:15:41,000 --> 02:15:44,000
but this freedom comes with you guessed it.

1697
02:15:44,000 --> 02:15:47,000
As Uncle Ben said it comes with responsibility.

1698
02:15:47,000 --> 02:15:52,000
In other words we are our own makers we craft our own self-identity

1699
02:15:52,000 --> 02:15:56,000
therefore we have to live with what we make of ourselves.

1700
02:15:56,000 --> 02:16:01,000
Unlike Hegel and Marx Sartre liberates individuals from the constraints of God

1701
02:16:01,000 --> 02:16:04,000
history traditions class and even human nature.

1702
02:16:04,000 --> 02:16:08,000
So today a new trend among homo sapiens is transgenderism

1703
02:16:08,000 --> 02:16:13,000
the idea that you can define your own gender identity based on your own feelings.

1704
02:16:13,000 --> 02:16:17,000
People feel they are in the wrong body and they change their gender

1705
02:16:17,000 --> 02:16:19,000
and an attempt to correct the incorrect.

1706
02:16:19,000 --> 02:16:22,000
This might have been difficult in a pre-existentialist era

1707
02:16:22,000 --> 02:16:26,000
but now it's widely accepted in most of the developed world

1708
02:16:26,000 --> 02:16:29,000
you can decide what your identity is.

1709
02:16:29,000 --> 02:16:33,000
Instead of your biology, society's history, tradition or norms defining you

1710
02:16:33,000 --> 02:16:38,000
you have the full control to make yourself and find your own life's purpose.

1711
02:16:38,000 --> 02:16:41,000
As I said with this freedom comes responsibility.

1712
02:16:42,000 --> 02:16:46,000
If you make mistake you have to own those mistakes don't blame others.

1713
02:16:46,000 --> 02:16:50,000
In other words if you build a bridge and it collapses you are responsible

1714
02:16:50,000 --> 02:16:54,000
and the same way you build your own identity if something goes wrong

1715
02:16:54,000 --> 02:16:56,000
you cannot blame others for it.

1716
02:16:56,000 --> 02:17:01,000
So Jean Paul Sartre's existentialist philosophy gave the individual the full autonomy

1717
02:17:01,000 --> 02:17:03,000
to make something of themselves.

1718
02:17:03,000 --> 02:17:07,000
For him it wasn't social history but your own individual history

1719
02:17:07,000 --> 02:17:10,000
that makes you your own free choices.

1720
02:17:11,000 --> 02:17:15,000
Slavojecek was born in Slovenia in 1949.

1721
02:17:15,000 --> 02:17:20,000
Today he is the most important figure who subscribes to a history based philosophy.

1722
02:17:20,000 --> 02:17:25,000
He identifies himself as Hegelian who argues that Marxism has failed miserably

1723
02:17:25,000 --> 02:17:29,000
because most Marxists today live in the past, too attached to history.

1724
02:17:29,000 --> 02:17:32,000
Today's Marxists blame history for their failure.

1725
02:17:32,000 --> 02:17:36,000
In other words he says that Marxists today have lost touch with reality

1726
02:17:36,000 --> 02:17:40,000
and live in the past like an old man who has failed in his life projects.

1727
02:17:40,000 --> 02:17:47,000
This failure is most visible in his own style as he uses comedy to cope with that failure.

1728
02:17:47,000 --> 02:17:50,000
His philosophy is based on philosophical irony.

1729
02:17:50,000 --> 02:17:53,000
Marxists believe in history and historical struggle.

1730
02:17:53,000 --> 02:17:56,000
The very history that these philosophers based their ideas

1731
02:17:56,000 --> 02:18:00,000
failed their attempt to create a truly socialist society.

1732
02:18:00,000 --> 02:18:05,000
So history failed the philosophical tradition that based its core philosophy on history.

1733
02:18:05,000 --> 02:18:09,000
Now that's ironic and so on and so on and so on you get the point.

1734
02:18:10,000 --> 02:18:14,000
So to sum up Hegel said we are the product of history that keeps progressing

1735
02:18:14,000 --> 02:18:22,000
and Marx said let's not study history but let's speed it up to get our final destination, a communist utopia.

1736
02:18:22,000 --> 02:18:28,000
Sartre argues forget about class history we are the product of our own individual history

1737
02:18:28,000 --> 02:18:30,000
in which we'll also find our purpose.

1738
02:18:30,000 --> 02:18:34,000
And finally Zhecek says history has failed us all.

1739
02:18:34,000 --> 02:18:36,000
We have not progressed but regressed.

1740
02:18:36,000 --> 02:18:40,000
So our history is nothing but a history of failed intelligence or rationality.

1741
02:18:40,000 --> 02:18:44,000
Next I'll discuss the other strand of philosophy that came out of Kant

1742
02:18:44,000 --> 02:18:46,000
through Schopenhauer, Kierkegaard and Nietzsche

1743
02:18:46,000 --> 02:18:52,000
which emphasizes not rationality or history or society but passion or will or human psyche

1744
02:18:52,000 --> 02:18:56,000
the mysterious subconscious world of psychological philosophy.

1745
02:19:00,000 --> 02:19:05,000
Previously I discussed a bunch of philosophy that put emphasis on historical and social changes

1746
02:19:05,000 --> 02:19:08,000
the main motivating factors for human actions.

1747
02:19:08,000 --> 02:19:14,000
For example philosophers like Hegel, Marx and Sartre argued that we are the product of history

1748
02:19:14,000 --> 02:19:18,000
either society's history or our own personal history.

1749
02:19:18,000 --> 02:19:24,000
In this segment I'll focus on the other branch of philosophy that is based on the individual human psyche

1750
02:19:24,000 --> 02:19:27,000
or the blind will that drives human actions.

1751
02:19:27,000 --> 02:19:32,000
In other words it's not the history or society but other mysterious forces inside us

1752
02:19:32,000 --> 02:19:34,000
like passion or the blind subconscious will.

1753
02:19:34,000 --> 02:19:40,000
The German philosopher Otto Schopenhauer who lived between 1788 and 1860

1754
02:19:40,000 --> 02:19:43,000
was firmly against Hegel's philosophy.

1755
02:19:43,000 --> 02:19:48,000
Schopenhauer took Kant's distinction between the noble world of phenomena

1756
02:19:48,000 --> 02:19:53,000
and the unknowable world of Númena to develop his own theory of will and representation.

1757
02:19:53,000 --> 02:19:56,000
Schopenhauer argued that there is no distinction between the two.

1758
02:19:56,000 --> 02:20:00,000
They are one in the same thing or two sides of the same coin.

1759
02:20:00,000 --> 02:20:03,000
He said there is one world which he called will.

1760
02:20:03,000 --> 02:20:06,000
But this will is mysterious and hard to understand.

1761
02:20:06,000 --> 02:20:08,000
It's built in inside us.

1762
02:20:08,000 --> 02:20:12,000
In other words all living beings and even non-living beings

1763
02:20:12,000 --> 02:20:16,000
come pre-assembled or pre-installed with this blind will.

1764
02:20:16,000 --> 02:20:20,000
Since it's built in inside each being we cannot fully know.

1765
02:20:20,000 --> 02:20:25,000
We can only know how it's represented or manifested to us but not the will itself.

1766
02:20:25,000 --> 02:20:30,000
The will itself is hidden from us all we see is its mere representation.

1767
02:20:30,000 --> 02:20:34,000
For Schopenhauer will is the blind driving force in the universe

1768
02:20:34,000 --> 02:20:37,000
and representation is our perception of that blind will.

1769
02:20:37,000 --> 02:20:40,000
In other words will is the essence of the universe

1770
02:20:40,000 --> 02:20:44,000
and we only see or understand its manifestation in us.

1771
02:20:44,000 --> 02:20:47,000
He called it will to life or passion for life

1772
02:20:47,000 --> 02:20:52,000
that we share with all living beings including animals and plants.

1773
02:20:52,000 --> 02:20:56,000
We all have an innate will to continue living.

1774
02:20:56,000 --> 02:20:59,000
Since the will itself is blind and universal

1775
02:20:59,000 --> 02:21:03,000
we each become its eye through which it looks out to the world.

1776
02:21:03,000 --> 02:21:07,000
Will is like a gigantic iceberg while our human intellect

1777
02:21:07,000 --> 02:21:10,000
or human perception of it is only the tip of that iceberg.

1778
02:21:10,000 --> 02:21:15,000
So Schopenhauer really went deeply psychological about human motivation.

1779
02:21:15,000 --> 02:21:17,000
Schopenhauer says it's impossible to know the will

1780
02:21:17,000 --> 02:21:21,000
because as soon as you observe it it becomes a representation of that will.

1781
02:21:21,000 --> 02:21:24,000
If you do not observe it then it is the will.

1782
02:21:24,000 --> 02:21:27,000
It's like in quantum mechanics your observation of a particle

1783
02:21:27,000 --> 02:21:30,000
changes the position of the particle.

1784
02:21:30,000 --> 02:21:33,000
In other words if you don't look it is there

1785
02:21:33,000 --> 02:21:35,000
but as soon as you look it changes position.

1786
02:21:35,000 --> 02:21:38,000
It's also a kind of catch-22.

1787
02:21:38,000 --> 02:21:40,000
To understand Schopenhauer's idea of will

1788
02:21:40,000 --> 02:21:43,000
is to imagine everything in the universe as one thing

1789
02:21:43,000 --> 02:21:47,000
let's say atoms that oscillates between everything that exists.

1790
02:21:47,000 --> 02:21:51,000
It appears to us as something that is not genuine thing

1791
02:21:51,000 --> 02:21:53,000
but a mere representation.

1792
02:21:53,000 --> 02:21:55,000
To fully understand Schopenhauer's will

1793
02:21:55,000 --> 02:21:58,000
it's important to mention the Buddhist idea of the self

1794
02:21:58,000 --> 02:22:00,000
as an illusion or mirage.

1795
02:22:00,000 --> 02:22:03,000
For the Buddhist soul is universal

1796
02:22:03,000 --> 02:22:07,000
but the self is a mere mirage we acquire in our lifetime.

1797
02:22:07,000 --> 02:22:11,000
In other words our essence is not the self we call me or I.

1798
02:22:11,000 --> 02:22:15,000
Schopenhauer too places the blind will at a much deeper place

1799
02:22:15,000 --> 02:22:17,000
than we understand or we can get to

1800
02:22:17,000 --> 02:22:19,000
and will only get a representation of it.

1801
02:22:19,000 --> 02:22:23,000
He also said that will is the cause of our human suffering.

1802
02:22:23,000 --> 02:22:27,000
Therefore Schopenhauer's often considered the father of pessimism.

1803
02:22:27,000 --> 02:22:30,000
Just like in Buddhism our ego desires things

1804
02:22:30,000 --> 02:22:32,000
and those desires makes us suffer

1805
02:22:32,000 --> 02:22:35,000
because we can never satisfy our desires fully.

1806
02:22:35,000 --> 02:22:38,000
Schopenhauer says since we have a body

1807
02:22:38,000 --> 02:22:41,000
we have a will that somehow controls us

1808
02:22:41,000 --> 02:22:43,000
and that causes us suffering.

1809
02:22:43,000 --> 02:22:46,000
So we are all at the mercy of this blind will

1810
02:22:46,000 --> 02:22:48,000
that urges us to do things.

1811
02:22:48,000 --> 02:22:50,000
The only way to cope with this suffering

1812
02:22:50,000 --> 02:22:52,000
is through intellect and art

1813
02:22:52,000 --> 02:22:55,000
which allows us to move to a state of non-existence

1814
02:22:55,000 --> 02:22:57,000
like in Buddhist Nirvana.

1815
02:22:57,000 --> 02:22:59,000
Artists while creating art

1816
02:22:59,000 --> 02:23:02,000
as well as us while enjoying that art

1817
02:23:02,000 --> 02:23:05,000
we all experience a moment of non-being

1818
02:23:05,000 --> 02:23:07,000
while in awe of its beauty.

1819
02:23:07,000 --> 02:23:09,000
When an art takes our breath away

1820
02:23:09,000 --> 02:23:12,000
we truly experience non-existence

1821
02:23:12,000 --> 02:23:14,000
a kind of blissful moment.

1822
02:23:14,000 --> 02:23:17,000
Schopenhauer influenced the German composer Richard Wagner

1823
02:23:17,000 --> 02:23:20,000
whose music represents Schopenhauer's philosophy.

1824
02:23:20,000 --> 02:23:24,000
For Schopenhauer music didn't represent the phenomenal world

1825
02:23:24,000 --> 02:23:27,000
therefore it was free from the will and urges

1826
02:23:27,000 --> 02:23:29,000
instead it fostered compassion.

1827
02:23:29,000 --> 02:23:32,000
Schopenhauer had a massive influence on novelists

1828
02:23:32,000 --> 02:23:34,000
and musicians of the 19th century.

1829
02:23:34,000 --> 02:23:37,000
He also influenced psychoanalysts

1830
02:23:37,000 --> 02:23:39,000
especially Sigmund Freud and Carl Jung.

1831
02:23:39,000 --> 02:23:42,000
Schopenhauer also dismissed the idea of God

1832
02:23:42,000 --> 02:23:44,000
and replaced God with the blind will

1833
02:23:44,000 --> 02:23:48,000
and this had an influence on our next philosopher.

1834
02:23:50,000 --> 02:23:52,000
The Danish philosopher Soren Kierkegaard

1835
02:23:52,000 --> 02:23:55,000
lived between 1813 and 1855.

1836
02:23:55,000 --> 02:23:58,000
He argued that our anxiety comes from our choices

1837
02:23:58,000 --> 02:24:01,000
or in other words our belief and complete freedom

1838
02:24:01,000 --> 02:24:02,000
to make choices.

1839
02:24:02,000 --> 02:24:05,000
In a world where everyone believes in God

1840
02:24:05,000 --> 02:24:07,000
where everything is caused by God

1841
02:24:07,000 --> 02:24:10,000
people accept it because there is no other choice.

1842
02:24:10,000 --> 02:24:12,000
In other words God tells you what to do

1843
02:24:12,000 --> 02:24:13,000
and what not to do.

1844
02:24:13,000 --> 02:24:15,000
You have no choice of your own.

1845
02:24:15,000 --> 02:24:18,000
But we live in a world where we no longer believe in God

1846
02:24:18,000 --> 02:24:20,000
so we have the freedom to choose

1847
02:24:20,000 --> 02:24:23,000
but this freedom comes at a massive psychological cost.

1848
02:24:23,000 --> 02:24:26,000
It makes us anxious about our choices

1849
02:24:26,000 --> 02:24:28,000
and the consequences of our choices.

1850
02:24:28,000 --> 02:24:31,000
When we are children we live a carefree life

1851
02:24:31,000 --> 02:24:33,000
because our parents take care of everything

1852
02:24:33,000 --> 02:24:36,000
and the same way a God fearing society

1853
02:24:36,000 --> 02:24:38,000
also lives in a kind of blissful ignorance.

1854
02:24:38,000 --> 02:24:41,000
Since God is dead or when parents die

1855
02:24:41,000 --> 02:24:44,000
we are responsible to make our own choices.

1856
02:24:44,000 --> 02:24:48,000
The psychological toll of making choices is immense on us.

1857
02:24:48,000 --> 02:24:51,000
For example, Hamlet agonizes over the question

1858
02:24:51,000 --> 02:24:54,000
of to be or not to be in Shakespeare's play.

1859
02:24:54,000 --> 02:24:57,000
Incidentally Hamlet was also a dain like Kierkegaard.

1860
02:24:57,000 --> 02:25:00,000
In the 19th century a hysteria was very prevalent

1861
02:25:00,000 --> 02:25:02,000
especially among women.

1862
02:25:02,000 --> 02:25:05,000
Today anxiety is more common among both men and women

1863
02:25:05,000 --> 02:25:08,000
so absolute freedom makes us anxious.

1864
02:25:08,000 --> 02:25:11,000
Kierkegaard himself never lost faith in God

1865
02:25:11,000 --> 02:25:14,000
but he saw freedom as good and bad.

1866
02:25:14,000 --> 02:25:16,000
While it makes us anxious and dizzy

1867
02:25:16,000 --> 02:25:19,000
it also allows us to make good moral choices.

1868
02:25:19,000 --> 02:25:21,000
His problem with Hegel's theory of history

1869
02:25:21,000 --> 02:25:24,000
was that it gave little room for individual freedom

1870
02:25:24,000 --> 02:25:27,000
because we were bound by the historical force.

1871
02:25:27,000 --> 02:25:30,000
In fact we suffer not because of the bigger forces in society

1872
02:25:30,000 --> 02:25:33,000
but we suffer through our own action

1873
02:25:33,000 --> 02:25:36,000
or choices we make as individuals.

1874
02:25:36,000 --> 02:25:39,000
So Schopenhauer said the blind will motivate us

1875
02:25:39,000 --> 02:25:42,000
while living us with minimum freedom of our own

1876
02:25:42,000 --> 02:25:46,000
and Kierkegaard said that little freedom induces anxiety in us.

1877
02:25:46,000 --> 02:25:51,000
Now these two philosophers come together in our next philosopher.

1878
02:25:53,000 --> 02:25:55,000
The German philosopher Friedrich Nietzsche

1879
02:25:55,000 --> 02:25:58,000
lived between 1844 and 1900.

1880
02:25:58,000 --> 02:26:01,000
He was a great admirer of Schopenhauer.

1881
02:26:01,000 --> 02:26:04,000
He accepted Schopenhauer's idea of the will

1882
02:26:04,000 --> 02:26:08,000
but he had a big problem how passive this will to life was.

1883
02:26:08,000 --> 02:26:11,000
Nietzsche argued that this will blinded maybe

1884
02:26:11,000 --> 02:26:15,000
can be harnessed and utilized for great purposes

1885
02:26:15,000 --> 02:26:18,000
artistic genius and philosophical flourishing.

1886
02:26:18,000 --> 02:26:20,000
He changed the passive will to life

1887
02:26:20,000 --> 02:26:23,000
into a proactive will to power.

1888
02:26:23,000 --> 02:26:25,000
In other words we are not here just to live

1889
02:26:25,000 --> 02:26:28,000
but we are here to grow, conquer and dominate.

1890
02:26:28,000 --> 02:26:32,000
Nature is based on competition not a state of blissfulness

1891
02:26:32,000 --> 02:26:34,000
or mere survival.

1892
02:26:34,000 --> 02:26:36,000
Nietzsche saw religion especially its morality

1893
02:26:36,000 --> 02:26:39,000
as the biggest obstacle for individuals to push boundaries

1894
02:26:39,000 --> 02:26:41,000
in order to achieve greatness.

1895
02:26:41,000 --> 02:26:43,000
Morality decides what's good what's bad

1896
02:26:43,000 --> 02:26:47,000
so society promotes certain values and restricts others.

1897
02:26:47,000 --> 02:26:50,000
Nietzsche saw this as a weak minded way of living

1898
02:26:50,000 --> 02:26:52,000
that promoted weak or slave mentality.

1899
02:26:52,000 --> 02:26:55,000
He instead proposed a more nature based approach

1900
02:26:55,000 --> 02:26:58,000
in which no morality can restrict innovation

1901
02:26:58,000 --> 02:27:02,000
probing artistic creativity and philosophical ideas.

1902
02:27:02,000 --> 02:27:04,000
Nietzsche wants to grow, dominate

1903
02:27:04,000 --> 02:27:07,000
while religions suppress and tame people.

1904
02:27:07,000 --> 02:27:09,000
Nietzsche proposed the idea of ubermensch

1905
02:27:09,000 --> 02:27:13,000
a being who has surpassed humanity into something else

1906
02:27:13,000 --> 02:27:16,000
a free-spread artist or a philosophical genius.

1907
02:27:16,000 --> 02:27:19,000
He is no longer bound by social values and norms

1908
02:27:19,000 --> 02:27:22,000
because he has shed his human qualities of weakness

1909
02:27:22,000 --> 02:27:25,000
and slave mentality and religious compassion.

1910
02:27:25,000 --> 02:27:28,000
He is released from all that into an enormous

1911
02:27:28,000 --> 02:27:31,000
creative energy and exuberance for life.

1912
02:27:31,000 --> 02:27:34,000
Nietzsche also saw western philosophy championing rationality

1913
02:27:34,000 --> 02:27:37,000
at the expense of passion and emotions.

1914
02:27:37,000 --> 02:27:40,000
For him, passion was as important as reason.

1915
02:27:40,000 --> 02:27:43,000
Reason is just a tool it provides us with technology

1916
02:27:43,000 --> 02:27:46,000
that makes life easier and more comfortable.

1917
02:27:46,000 --> 02:27:48,000
But reason cannot motivate us to do things

1918
02:27:48,000 --> 02:27:50,000
that are daring and courageous.

1919
02:27:50,000 --> 02:27:53,000
Instead rationality makes us risk averse.

1920
02:27:53,000 --> 02:27:56,000
This timidness leads us to a hiddenism

1921
02:27:56,000 --> 02:27:59,000
in which we only seek pleasure and avoid pain.

1922
02:27:59,000 --> 02:28:02,000
This is a kind of nihilistic self-indulgence

1923
02:28:02,000 --> 02:28:05,000
that makes you lazy and self-centered.

1924
02:28:05,000 --> 02:28:08,000
Human passion on the other hand motivates us to do things

1925
02:28:08,000 --> 02:28:11,000
conquer the world and topple mountains.

1926
02:28:11,000 --> 02:28:13,000
So Nietzsche's philosophy was based on human passion

1927
02:28:13,000 --> 02:28:16,000
or the will to power to surpass the current humans

1928
02:28:16,000 --> 02:28:18,000
into a great genius.

1929
02:28:18,000 --> 02:28:20,000
Nietzsche didn't believe in equality either

1930
02:28:20,000 --> 02:28:23,000
because only a handful of people could become

1931
02:28:23,000 --> 02:28:26,000
great artists and genius philosophers.

1932
02:28:26,000 --> 02:28:29,000
Not everyone has original ideas.

1933
02:28:29,000 --> 02:28:32,000
So to sum up, Schopenhauer placed human motivation

1934
02:28:32,000 --> 02:28:35,000
on the blind in a twill while Kierkegaard said

1935
02:28:35,000 --> 02:28:38,000
our anxiety comes from the little freedom we experience

1936
02:28:38,000 --> 02:28:41,000
and Nietzsche argued we're driven by will to power

1937
02:28:41,000 --> 02:28:44,000
or passion to push society forward and innovate.

1938
02:28:44,000 --> 02:28:47,000
Today's sociology and psychology have replaced

1939
02:28:47,000 --> 02:28:50,000
philosophy when it comes to human motivation.

1940
02:28:50,000 --> 02:28:53,000
One of the leading voices of psychology is

1941
02:28:53,000 --> 02:28:56,000
Jordan Peterson who was born in 1962

1942
02:28:56,000 --> 02:28:59,000
and has adopted YouTube as his platform.

1943
02:28:59,000 --> 02:29:02,000
Another contemporary voice is the Indian Yogi

1944
02:29:02,000 --> 02:29:05,000
Sadguru. Peterson believes in human passion

1945
02:29:05,000 --> 02:29:08,000
and faith telling young people to take individual

1946
02:29:08,000 --> 02:29:11,000
responsibility. Unlike Zezek, Peterson doesn't

1947
02:29:11,000 --> 02:29:14,000
see the world through group identity like class or gender

1948
02:29:14,000 --> 02:29:17,000
but through the lens of the individual. His idea

1949
02:29:17,000 --> 02:29:20,000
of perception is somewhat similar to Schopenhauer's will

1950
02:29:20,000 --> 02:29:23,000
and representation. Sadguru, an Indian Yogi Guru

1951
02:29:23,000 --> 02:29:26,000
on the other hand argues that today's world is shaped

1952
02:29:26,000 --> 02:29:29,000
by materialism and people have conflated

1953
02:29:29,000 --> 02:29:32,000
the desire for more with happiness. Our goal

1954
02:29:32,000 --> 02:29:35,000
is no longer happiness but to have more.

1955
02:29:35,000 --> 02:29:38,000
He argues it's time we reach a higher level of intelligence

1956
02:29:38,000 --> 02:29:41,000
